248
00:23:13,935 --> 00:23:16,313
Cartwheels, handsprings.

249
00:23:16,605 --> 00:23:19,774
Who's got the moxie
to just take over like that?

250
00:23:19,941 --> 00:23:24,237
- You gave them what they wanted, Bon.
- But I never even got to my soliloquy.

251
00:23:25,906 --> 00:23:29,075
Maybe I'll never get to my soliloquy.

252
00:23:32,621 --> 00:23:35,415
I will never forget this day.

253
00:23:36,917 --> 00:23:41,087
And now Miss Bonnie Parker
would like to sing a song for her father.

254
00:23:46,927 --> 00:23:49,512
This was my daddy's favorite song.

255
00:24:26,383 --> 00:24:28,051
Evening, Mrs. Parker.

256
00:24:28,218 --> 00:24:32,138
I'd like to see your daughter,
as I've got intentions to take her out.

257
00:24:32,806 --> 00:24:34,557
- Is she expecting you?
- No, ma'am.

258
00:24:35,475 --> 00:24:37,435
We've never really met.

259
00:24:39,145 --> 00:24:40,939
Bonnie?

260
00:24:41,106 --> 00:24:43,775
Believe you've got a gentleman caller.

261
00:24:44,025 --> 00:24:45,902
- Mr...?
- Barrow.

262
00:24:46,069 --> 00:24:48,697
Clyde "Champion" Barrow.

263
00:24:55,245 --> 00:24:57,455
You were at my wedding.

264
00:24:57,622 --> 00:24:59,374
I was.

265
00:25:01,084 --> 00:25:02,752
Friend of the groom's'?

266
00:25:02,919 --> 00:25:05,964
You talked to Roy recently, have you?

267
00:25:08,633 --> 00:25:11,219
Guess you're not one much
to let the kettle cool.

268
00:25:11,386 --> 00:25:12,971
Not me.

269
00:25:14,472 --> 00:25:16,599
Is this car yours?

270
00:25:16,766 --> 00:25:19,227
Tonight it sure is.

271
00:25:27,527 --> 00:25:30,405
Keep them both on the wheel, huh?

272
00:25:32,032 --> 00:25:33,658
All right.

273
00:26:18,203 --> 00:26:19,287
What can I get you?

274
00:26:19,454 --> 00:26:22,999
- Two fingers of whiskey'd be nice for me.
- Whiskey sounds good.

275
00:26:23,166 --> 00:26:26,377
- How about you put a little soda in hers?
- Yes, sir.

276
00:26:28,546 --> 00:26:31,216
You gonna be all right for a minute,
Bonnie Parker?

277
00:26:31,382 --> 00:26:32,842
Sure. Where you going?

278
00:26:33,009 --> 00:26:37,097
Well, music's calling,
I'm just answering the bell.

279
00:28:12,775 --> 00:28:16,946
I don't know if I can remember a night
that can hold e candle to this.

280
00:28:17,113 --> 00:28:19,741
It's almost like it's meant to be.

281
00:28:19,908 --> 00:28:21,951
Like you and me.

282
00:28:22,660 --> 00:28:27,624
You can't talk about meant to be
when we haven't even kissed yet.

283
00:28:30,835 --> 00:28:33,129
I didn't say I wanted to kiss you.

284
00:28:33,296 --> 00:28:35,298
Yeah, you did.

285
00:28:42,222 --> 00:28:47,018
So you're convinced after one date
and one middling kiss...

286
00:28:47,185 --> 00:28:50,104
...that I'm the girl's gonna make
your dreams come true?

287
00:28:50,271 --> 00:28:51,814
Nope.

288
00:28:51,981 --> 00:28:55,652
I'm convinced I'm the man's
gonna make yours come true.

289
00:29:15,213 --> 00:29:17,840
I get clear, I'll come calling.

290
00:29:20,218 --> 00:29:21,803
Hold it! Stop!

291
00:29:22,637 --> 00:29:26,307
- All right, don't nobody move!
- Get out of the way!

292
00:29:27,558 --> 00:29:29,560
- Move!
- Get on the back door!

293
00:29:29,727 --> 00:29:32,563
We're shutting the joint down!
Don't nobody move!

294
00:29:32,730 --> 00:29:35,733
You're all under arrest!
This is an illegal establishment!

295
00:29:35,900 --> 00:29:37,986
Don't nobody move,
and nobody gets hurt!

296
00:29:38,152 --> 00:29:40,196
Where do you think you're going?

297
00:29:43,283 --> 00:29:44,659
I know you.

298
00:29:44,826 --> 00:29:46,953
He's the other joker
who stole that safe.

299
00:29:52,709 --> 00:29:55,169
You want a slice of Cobbler with that joe,
Ted?

300
00:29:55,336 --> 00:29:57,714
Just coffee today, Bonnie.

301
00:29:59,465 --> 00:30:01,384
Something on your mind?

302
00:30:02,427 --> 00:30:04,679
Yeah, actually.

303
00:30:05,096 --> 00:30:08,725
Heard you got dragged
out of a Speakeasy last night.

304
00:30:08,891 --> 00:30:11,561
Who you seeing
taking you to a place like that?

305
00:30:11,728 --> 00:30:13,688
What do you think
your mama would say?

306
00:30:13,855 --> 00:30:17,191
What are you gonna do, tell her?

307
00:30:17,358 --> 00:30:18,735
No.

308
00:30:21,195 --> 00:30:22,864
Herald might.

309
00:30:55,563 --> 00:30:57,648
Things slow down at Marco's'?

310
00:30:58,524 --> 00:30:59,859
Nothing new about that.

311
00:31:00,026 --> 00:31:03,029
It's nice of you
to try to spare me the indignity...

312
00:31:03,196 --> 00:31:06,074
...but Mrs. Haskell called
as soon as she saw it.

313
00:31:06,366 --> 00:31:09,786
She tried to sound so distraught.
She got on the party line...

314
00:31:09,952 --> 00:31:12,955
...and clucked about my
wayward daughter to all the hens.

315
00:31:13,122 --> 00:31:16,459
Well, you're the one that let him in.

316
00:31:18,586 --> 00:31:20,588
Get that out of here.

317
00:31:28,388 --> 00:31:30,431
Choices made.

318
00:31:30,640 --> 00:31:34,060
Roads gone down
or turned away from.

319
00:31:34,394 --> 00:31:35,853
From my experience...

320
00:31:36,020 --> 00:31:40,566
...trying to figure out why people
do the things they do defies ell logic.

321
00:31:49,951 --> 00:31:51,202
Clyde Barrow.

322
00:31:56,416 --> 00:31:59,669
And Bonnie Parker.

323
00:32:06,426 --> 00:32:08,594
Clyde and Bonnie.

324
00:32:13,975 --> 00:32:15,226
Bonnie and Clyde.

325
00:32:18,980 --> 00:32:22,066
Bonnie and Clyde.

326
00:32:29,949 --> 00:32:32,410
Maybe if somebody left open
a door they shut...

327
00:32:32,577 --> 00:32:36,956
...maybe if we were living in times of
milk and honey instead of grit and piss...

328
00:32:37,123 --> 00:32:40,835
...Bonnie might have just faded off
into obscurity.

329
00:32:42,420 --> 00:32:45,506
Maybe if they weren't celebrating
anyone who dared rise up.

330
00:32:48,968 --> 00:32:54,223
Hell, maybe if I wouldn't have promised
to make all her dreams come true...

331
00:32:54,390 --> 00:32:56,934
...Bonnie would've forgotten
all about me.

332
00:32:57,602 --> 00:32:59,812
Lord knows she should've.

333
00:33:52,448 --> 00:33:54,075
Can I help you with something?

334
00:33:54,242 --> 00:33:57,411
I hope so.
I wanted to see one of your prisoners.

335
00:33:57,578 --> 00:33:58,788
Mr. Clyde Barrow.

336
00:33:59,413 --> 00:34:01,249
I'm Clyde's wife.

337
00:34:01,415 --> 00:34:02,833
That's a nice ring.

338
00:34:03,000 --> 00:34:06,128
And I'd like to help,
but we're just a holding tank here.

339
00:34:06,295 --> 00:34:09,674
There's no visitation allowed,
even spousal.

340
00:34:13,553 --> 00:34:16,722
- Oh, ma'am, you all right?
- I don't know.

341
00:34:16,889 --> 00:34:19,809
We hadn't even gone
on our honeymoon yet.

342
00:34:20,351 --> 00:34:23,437
And he's gonna be sent away
to hard time, I know it.

343
00:34:23,854 --> 00:34:27,942
And I'm gonna be left alone
for God knows how long.

344
00:34:33,114 --> 00:34:35,241
Your wife's here, Barrow.

345
00:34:36,242 --> 00:34:37,827
Hello, honey.

346
00:34:38,286 --> 00:34:39,870
Let's make it short and sweet.

347
00:34:41,038 --> 00:34:43,457
Jesus, Bonnie,
I can't believe you're here.

348
00:34:43,624 --> 00:34:45,626
What are you doing?

349
00:34:46,752 --> 00:34:47,878
Where'd you get that?

350
00:34:48,045 --> 00:34:50,172
- It isn't important.
- Bullshit, it's not.

351
00:34:50,339 --> 00:34:54,510
- Don't want you getting mixed up in this.
- For Pete's sake, Clyde, take the gun.

352
00:34:54,885 --> 00:34:56,220
Don't take it.

353
00:34:56,387 --> 00:35:00,141
- We'll be in federal lockup by Friday.
- Well, nobody asked you, cracker.

354
00:35:00,725 --> 00:35:02,268
You got one minute.

355
00:35:03,019 --> 00:35:06,897
Clyde Barrow,
if anything's meant to be between us...

356
00:35:07,064 --> 00:35:09,692
...I think it better start being now.

357
00:35:18,492 --> 00:35:20,745
- it's empty.
- Well, I didn't know that.

358
00:35:21,537 --> 00:35:23,706
And neither will they.

359
00:35:23,873 --> 00:35:28,502
I borrowed my uncle's car. I'll be waiting
by Miller's Creek until midnight.

360
00:35:32,214 --> 00:35:34,717
Lord have mercy.

361
00:35:46,312 --> 00:35:47,563
Stop!

362
00:35:49,690 --> 00:35:52,026
Ain't nowhere for you to go!

363
00:35:53,110 --> 00:35:54,153
Hold it right there!

364
00:35:56,614 --> 00:35:59,617
- We got you, Turner!
- Barrow!

365
00:36:01,369 --> 00:36:02,828
That's it.

366
00:36:05,915 --> 00:36:07,083
Move over.

367
00:36:07,249 --> 00:36:09,126
That's the way.

368
00:36:09,293 --> 00:36:11,712
Barrow! Don't you do it!

369
00:36:22,765 --> 00:36:24,642
Ain't even in third yet.

370
00:36:24,809 --> 00:36:26,310
I got your suit in the back.

371
00:36:26,477 --> 00:36:28,896
Even got us a place to go.

372
00:37:10,354 --> 00:37:11,480
What?

373
00:37:12,857 --> 00:37:16,485
I used to keep a horseshoe under my bed
for good luck.

374
00:37:19,071 --> 00:37:21,657
You aren't the only one feeling lucky,
Mr. Barrow.

375
00:38:03,240 --> 00:38:06,160
- Can I help you?
- Yeah, I bent the rim on my Ford.

376
00:38:06,327 --> 00:38:08,329
You do any wheelwrighting?

377
00:38:08,496 --> 00:38:11,248
Yeah, I'll help you out
as soon as I'm done with him.

378
00:38:16,337 --> 00:38:21,133
- That's your horse out front?
- I think I'm more his than he's mine.

379
00:38:21,425 --> 00:38:23,719
Not a bad idea
if you're the man riding him.

380
00:38:23,886 --> 00:38:27,431
Yeah, I sit around eating
more than I used to.

381
00:38:27,598 --> 00:38:30,059
It's one of the downsides of retirement.

382
00:38:30,226 --> 00:38:33,187
- What'd you used to do?
- I was a Texas Ranger.

383
00:38:35,272 --> 00:38:36,357
You don't say.

384
00:38:38,651 --> 00:38:43,072
I bet wrongdoers hated having you
with that big mount of yours on their ass.

385
00:38:43,239 --> 00:38:45,658
That'll be two bits, Mr. Hamer.

386
00:38:45,908 --> 00:38:47,409
Hamer?

387
00:38:50,704 --> 00:38:54,291
- Are you Frank Hamer?
- I used to be.

388
00:38:58,295 --> 00:39:00,172
Frank Hamer.

389
00:39:02,424 --> 00:39:05,761
- You didn't tell me what you do, son.
- Oh, I'm looking for work.

390
00:39:05,928 --> 00:39:09,640
Pretty good with cars, if you know
anybody looking for a grease monkey.

391
00:39:09,807 --> 00:39:11,976
I'll keep an eye out.
You seem personable.

392
00:39:12,142 --> 00:39:15,771
You don't find a job right away,
don't stop looking.

393
00:39:16,105 --> 00:39:19,483
A lot of people falling in the wrong line
of endeavor these days.

394
00:39:19,650 --> 00:39:22,278
Not that I'm suggesting you would.

395
00:39:22,611 --> 00:39:24,613
Appreciate the fatherly.

396
00:39:25,114 --> 00:39:26,615
Nice to meet you, Mr. Hamer.

397
00:39:29,285 --> 00:39:32,496
Rumor had it
Hamer could see #red bullets...

398
00:39:32,663 --> 00:39:34,874
...hear sounds before they were made.

399
00:39:35,040 --> 00:39:39,378
The press had even given a name
to his .45 Colt: Old Lucky.

400
00:39:39,545 --> 00:39:43,757
Which had nothing to do with the chances
of the outlaws who met up with Hamer.

401
00:39:44,341 --> 00:39:46,677
Right then, I made a pact with myself

402
00:39:46,844 --> 00:39:52,808
One job to give me and Bonnie a stake.
That was gonna be it.

403
00:39:56,854 --> 00:39:58,230
- Clyde?
- Yeah?

404
00:39:58,397 --> 00:39:59,815
Some guy's here to see you.

405
00:39:59,982 --> 00:40:02,067
Says his name's Methvin.

406
00:40:02,234 --> 00:40:04,653
- Good.
- What's he here for?

407
00:40:04,820 --> 00:40:07,239
The oil refinery job.

408
00:40:07,406 --> 00:40:09,783
But I thought you said
that was a two-man job.

409
00:40:09,950 --> 00:40:13,287
Yeah, it is, and he's the other man.

410
00:40:14,121 --> 00:40:16,165
What are you talking about?

411
00:40:16,373 --> 00:40:19,627
We planned that together.
I'm the one that did the casing.

412
00:40:19,793 --> 00:40:21,045
More than you should've.

413
00:40:21,211 --> 00:40:24,965
Methvin's got experience. It's gonna
be better for everybody, all right?

414
00:40:25,132 --> 00:40:27,635
Now, could you please
get me my pants?

415
00:40:32,222 --> 00:40:34,516
Get me my damn pants.

416
00:40:43,817 --> 00:40:47,446
- Excuse me, what's your name again?
- Methvin, Henry Methvin.

417
00:40:47,613 --> 00:40:50,574
Well, Clyde's changed his mind,
Henry.

418
00:40:50,741 --> 00:40:53,202
- He won't be needing you.
- Now, hang on, Bonnie.

419
00:40:53,369 --> 00:40:55,371
Hey, Henry. Hey, good to see you.

420
00:40:55,537 --> 00:40:58,457
- Just a little misunderstanding.
- Damn it, Clyde Barrow.

421
00:40:58,624 --> 00:41:02,211
We had an agreement
to do this together, me and you.

422
00:41:02,378 --> 00:41:07,049
Yeah, well, you gonna carry a gun with
these heels and that little purse of yours?

423
00:41:07,216 --> 00:41:10,594
- Those are nice shoes.
- What if you need to run in these shoes...

424
00:41:10,761 --> 00:41:13,555
...because somebody's trying
to put buckshot up our asses?

425
00:41:13,722 --> 00:41:18,018
Well, I'll kick them the hell off.
Now, tell Mythman here...

426
00:41:18,185 --> 00:41:20,854
...that we don't need him.

427
00:41:23,440 --> 00:41:25,818
Fine. Fine.

428
00:41:25,985 --> 00:41:27,653
All right. All right, already.

429
00:41:27,820 --> 00:41:29,488
All right, heretofore...

430
00:41:29,655 --> 00:41:35,285
...the oil refinery is a three-man job.

431
00:41:35,953 --> 00:41:37,955
Are you happy now?

432
00:41:38,914 --> 00:41:40,916
- Well, show him a smile.
- Yeah.

433
00:41:41,083 --> 00:41:42,543
All right.

434
00:41:58,851 --> 00:42:02,021
Clyde, the turn to the oil refinery's
back there.

435
00:42:02,187 --> 00:42:05,065
But the guns are stashed out here.

436
00:42:05,232 --> 00:42:06,817
- Out here?
- Yeah.

437
00:42:06,984 --> 00:42:08,402
Where?

438
00:42:08,736 --> 00:42:10,487
Just yonder.

439
00:42:19,872 --> 00:42:22,916
That old wagon right there,
just under the hay.

440
00:42:24,710 --> 00:42:26,420
You want me to get them?

441
00:42:26,587 --> 00:42:29,256
You want to be a part
of this three-man job or not?

442
00:42:38,682 --> 00:42:39,767
In here?

443
00:42:39,933 --> 00:42:42,269
Pick you up in a couple hours
when it's over!

444
00:42:42,436 --> 00:42:43,854
Clyde!

445
00:42:44,021 --> 00:42:45,314
Clyde, you...!

446
00:42:45,481 --> 00:42:47,232
Goddamn it, Clyde!

447
00:42:50,360 --> 00:42:53,113
I think she could've managed
the lookout.

448
00:44:03,392 --> 00:44:05,394
Need a lift, miss?

449
00:44:08,105 --> 00:44:09,982
What'd they do?

450
00:44:10,149 --> 00:44:11,942
Broke into an oil refinery.

451
00:44:12,109 --> 00:44:15,070
- Tried to take the payroll.
- Would've gotten it too...

452
00:44:15,237 --> 00:44:18,532
- ...if we'd had a lookout.
- No lookout.

453
00:44:19,199 --> 00:44:20,659
Imagine that.

454
00:44:24,454 --> 00:44:25,956
Huntsville's bad.

455
00:44:26,123 --> 00:44:30,002
But unless you get Eastham Farm,
you'll be all right, which you shouldn't.

456
00:44:30,169 --> 00:44:32,713
Small-time stuff you done
and being only...

457
00:44:32,880 --> 00:44:35,883
- How old are you?
- Twenty-one.

458
00:44:36,049 --> 00:44:39,303
Unless somebody screws up
or you bone the warden's daughter...

459
00:44:39,469 --> 00:44:41,430
...neither of you will get the Farm.

460
00:44:42,097 --> 00:44:44,224
I'm Bud Russell.

461
00:44:44,725 --> 00:44:47,603
And I'm tougher than all
you guys put together.

462
00:44:47,769 --> 00:44:50,689
Driven this chariot
over one-and-a-half million miles...

463
00:44:50,856 --> 00:44:53,066
...and only lost one con in all that time.

464
00:44:53,233 --> 00:44:55,485
And that eats at me
every single minute.

465
00:44:55,652 --> 00:44:58,238
Do not think
you're gonna be number two.

466
00:44:58,405 --> 00:45:01,116
- Hell you looking at?
- I ain't looking at nothing.

467
00:45:01,283 --> 00:45:05,078
- You got attitude, boy?
- I ain't got no attitude.

468
00:45:05,245 --> 00:45:08,582
I'm thrilled to be here,
what with you the warm welcoming sort.

469
00:45:12,336 --> 00:45:15,923
You're shit. Shit going nowhere.

470
00:45:16,131 --> 00:45:18,967
Get your worthless ass
in that one-way wagon.

471
00:45:26,433 --> 00:45:29,937
Pretty sure that just bought you
the Farm.

472
00:45:52,292 --> 00:45:55,295
You tell me you're going to church,
and you wind up here.

473
00:45:56,922 --> 00:46:00,676
You snuck him in that gun, didn't you?
Oh, don't look at me like that.

474
00:46:00,842 --> 00:46:04,221
You had any sense, you'd know
the best thing could've happened...

475
00:46:04,388 --> 00:46:06,223
...was he got hauled right back in.

476
00:46:07,015 --> 00:46:10,477
There is no reason a girl like you
cannot find a good man.

477
00:46:19,528 --> 00:46:21,863
Don't you go into
one of your fits over him.

478
00:46:22,030 --> 00:46:24,241
Do not let that happen.

479
00:46:24,408 --> 00:46:27,619
Settle your breathing,
like I taught you, you hear me?

480
00:46:33,166 --> 00:46:35,043
He's better for me than Roy, Mama.

481
00:46:35,210 --> 00:46:39,172
That, my daughter, isn't saying,
excuse my French, jack-the-F-shit.

482
00:46:39,339 --> 00:46:42,884
You deserve yourself
way better than Clyde Barrow.

483
00:46:45,554 --> 00:46:48,557
Ted Hinton told me
they gave him 14 years.

484
00:46:48,724 --> 00:46:50,475
You need to stop this.

485
00:46:50,642 --> 00:46:53,145
You need to look me in the eye...

486
00:46:53,312 --> 00:46:57,733
...and tell me you won't waste another
moment thinking about that boy.

487
00:47:07,409 --> 00:47:09,328
Pick up the pace!

488
00:47:17,127 --> 00:47:20,380
Man, Honolulu ain't got nothing
on this place.

489
00:47:22,549 --> 00:47:24,551
Get digging, Barrow!

490
00:47:27,471 --> 00:47:30,182
Get on deep in that ditch, boy!

491
00:47:45,280 --> 00:47:47,532
Think he's getting
sweet on you, Clyde?

492
00:47:47,699 --> 00:47:51,787
I don't know what's worse, the high rider's
whip or the big guy's affections.

493
00:47:52,245 --> 00:47:54,247
I'll take the high rider.

494
00:48:03,715 --> 00:48:07,010
Hey, Sunday after church,
my parents are having a picnic.

495
00:48:07,177 --> 00:48:09,471
My dad makes killer ribs.

496
00:48:09,721 --> 00:48:11,640
Not a big rib girl, Ted.

497
00:48:11,807 --> 00:48:15,519
Well, now, you don't have to eat.
There'd be... There'd be plenty to do.

498
00:48:15,685 --> 00:48:19,856
You know, I do some barbershop
with the boys at Dallas P.D.

499
00:48:20,023 --> 00:48:22,859
I know you're into musicals,
maybe you'd like it.

500
00:48:23,026 --> 00:48:24,861
Well ....

501
00:48:25,028 --> 00:48:27,155
I'll think about it, huh?

502
00:48:47,259 --> 00:48:48,552
- Thanks, Ted.
- Hey.

503
00:48:48,718 --> 00:48:50,971
Before you go, I was...

504
00:48:51,263 --> 00:48:53,306
I was thinking maybe we should kiss.

505
00:48:55,142 --> 00:48:56,768
Ted...

506
00:48:57,436 --> 00:49:02,357
...I'm not gonna listen to you sing,
or catch any more rides home with you.

507
00:49:03,191 --> 00:49:06,653
L... I like you, but nothing...

508
00:49:06,820 --> 00:49:08,447
...more.

509
00:49:10,615 --> 00:49:13,118
Well, I hope we can always be friends.

510
00:49:21,460 --> 00:49:24,171
Got enough darn friends.

511
00:49:38,101 --> 00:49:40,103
The hell you doing?

512
00:49:40,270 --> 00:49:44,065
- It was itching to be smelled.
- Yeah? Smell these.

513
00:49:48,737 --> 00:49:51,615
I hope you don't mind
that I write every day.

514
00:49:51,781 --> 00:49:54,868
But it's the only way for me
to cope with the loneliness...

515
00:49:55,035 --> 00:49:57,787
your incarceration
has visited upon me.

516
00:49:58,622 --> 00:50:01,374
I wonder what your days are like.

517
00:50:03,835 --> 00:50:07,422
Hope things there at Eastham
aren't as bad as folks say.

518
00:50:19,226 --> 00:50:23,104
And I hope the knowledge that
you've got a woman waiting for you...

519
00:50:23,271 --> 00:50:27,400
...makes it somehow more tolerable.

520
00:50:57,931 --> 00:51:00,850
But I hope these poetic stanzas
I've authored for you...

521
00:51:01,017 --> 00:51:03,103
...will bring some solace
to your time there.

522
00:51:06,815 --> 00:51:11,528
And she thought of herself
As only a stone

523
00:51:11,695 --> 00:51:15,198
Drifting the cosmos so terribly alone

524
00:51:16,157 --> 00:51:20,036
Days turned to years and eons
And still

525
00:51:20,203 --> 00:51:24,374
She found not her orbit
No gravity until

526
00:51:26,459 --> 00:51:30,380
The music of the spheres
Revealed it clear

527
00:51:31,464 --> 00:51:34,801
Spinning alone
And suddenly so near

528
00:51:36,886 --> 00:51:41,099
The moon found her earth
They danced all that night

529
00:51:43,101 --> 00:51:45,437
And forever they would

530
00:51:46,354 --> 00:51:48,773
Because that's what was right

531
00:52:16,384 --> 00:52:19,387
Stop standing around! Get to work!

532
00:52:40,575 --> 00:52:45,246
So the incident with Mr. Hamilton
was just an unfortunate accident?

533
00:52:45,413 --> 00:52:48,333
No, sir, it was a very painful one.

534
00:52:48,750 --> 00:52:51,544
Yeah. That's some nice work there.

535
00:52:51,711 --> 00:52:55,006
You ever think about mounting
any wayward inmates?

536
00:52:55,173 --> 00:52:57,592
On the wall, I mean.

537
00:52:59,052 --> 00:53:03,723
You know, I voted no
on the leniency owing to your injury.

538
00:53:04,599 --> 00:53:06,267
But my vote's but one of seven.

539
00:53:06,434 --> 00:53:10,146
I'm sorry you're in the minority there,
but I just want to thank you...

540
00:53:10,313 --> 00:53:14,067
...for all the lessons I learned
in this lovely facility.

541
00:53:14,234 --> 00:53:17,487
Yeah, you won't be seeing
Clyde Barrow again.

542
00:53:17,696 --> 00:53:20,281
Oddly, I believe I will.

543
00:53:21,741 --> 00:53:23,368
I'm sure you know that...

544
00:53:23,535 --> 00:53:28,331
...you were near to pardon even if you
had kept all ten of your little piggies.

545
00:53:28,498 --> 00:53:30,792
Your mother
and a gal named Bonnie Parker...

546
00:53:30,959 --> 00:53:34,587
...have been writing letters
to the governor on your behalf.

547
00:53:35,130 --> 00:53:38,216
Apparently, he was about
to have me send you home.

548
00:53:45,598 --> 00:53:47,016
Oh, Barrow?

549
00:53:48,810 --> 00:53:50,729
Hope you don't mind.

550
00:53:50,895 --> 00:53:52,605
I kept one.

551
00:53:59,612 --> 00:54:02,991
Why didn't somebody tell me
the governor was about to pardon me?

552
00:54:03,158 --> 00:54:06,453
Well, the notion one of us had
was to keep it a surprise.

553
00:54:06,619 --> 00:54:09,914
Well, l... I thought it'd be nice.

554
00:54:10,623 --> 00:54:12,959
I love surprises.

555
00:54:15,003 --> 00:54:16,963
Well, I do too.

556
00:54:17,297 --> 00:54:19,215
Maybe you ought to let Bonnie drive.

557
00:54:19,382 --> 00:54:22,510
She's the one who borrowed the oar
from some friend of hers.

558
00:54:22,677 --> 00:54:26,890
It ain't like my damn neck's
broken, Mama. I can drive.

559
00:54:47,911 --> 00:54:51,206
You're gonna come in, aren't you?
Your daddy'd want to see you.

560
00:54:51,372 --> 00:54:53,208
No, I'll probably come by Sunday.

561
00:54:53,374 --> 00:54:56,085
Get some of that
wonderful ham of yours.

562
00:54:56,836 --> 00:54:58,421
What?

563
00:54:59,214 --> 00:55:01,007
Just don't know.

564
00:55:01,174 --> 00:55:04,677
Just don't know that she's
gonna be good for you, Clyde.

565
00:55:06,471 --> 00:55:08,515
No, she's fine.

566
00:55:10,141 --> 00:55:14,854
Now, maybe she don't measure up
to you, but trust me...

567
00:55:15,021 --> 00:55:18,316
...Bonnie's more than good enough
for me, all right?

568
00:55:48,805 --> 00:55:50,139
Bonnie?

569
00:55:51,808 --> 00:55:54,477
No need to rush things.

570
00:56:13,371 --> 00:56:15,999
Probably sounds crazy.

571
00:56:16,165 --> 00:56:20,003
Guy like me, convict and all...

572
00:56:20,753 --> 00:56:23,673
...but I ain't afraid
of making a commitment.

573
00:56:24,674 --> 00:56:27,719
I ain't afraid of making a baby.

574
00:56:29,888 --> 00:56:32,390
I'm giving up criming.
I'm going straight-arrow.

575
00:56:32,557 --> 00:56:34,559
I want to do it for you.

576
00:56:35,852 --> 00:56:38,771
I don't know how to say this,
but I sort of ....

577
00:56:38,938 --> 00:56:41,232
I seen our future.

578
00:56:42,483 --> 00:56:45,153
I seen us in a big white house...

579
00:56:45,320 --> 00:56:47,864
...with big columns...

580
00:56:48,031 --> 00:56:51,117
...on the prettiest lake you ever saw.

581
00:56:51,284 --> 00:56:54,162
I'm gonna build you that house, Bon.

582
00:56:55,121 --> 00:56:58,374
And we gonna fill it with as many
little ones as you want.

583
00:57:03,087 --> 00:57:05,548
That is, if that's what you want.

584
00:57:05,757 --> 00:57:08,134
Of course it's what I want.

585
00:57:09,093 --> 00:57:13,640
I just didn't expect we'd start
the making-babies part just yet.

586
00:57:15,767 --> 00:57:19,187
Want some time
with just the two of us first.

587
00:57:20,897 --> 00:57:23,066
If that's all right with you.

588
00:58:03,022 --> 00:58:05,400
How much you think
they'd sell that for?

589
00:58:05,566 --> 00:58:07,276
That house?

590
00:58:07,443 --> 00:58:09,821
Probably like 5000.

591
00:58:10,196 --> 00:58:12,824
Seems like it might as well be a million.

592
00:58:14,409 --> 00:58:17,203
How do you reckon
we get that kind of money?

593
00:58:17,370 --> 00:58:21,666
- I don't know. I can find work.
- Well, raising kids isn't Cheap either.

594
00:58:21,833 --> 00:58:24,293
There's doctor bills and clothes.

595
00:58:25,461 --> 00:58:28,589
You spend a lot of money
on clothes for girls.

596
00:58:28,756 --> 00:58:31,801
And day-laboring ain't gonna be
enough for all that.

597
00:58:32,552 --> 00:58:35,722
I know cars. If I could get someone
to front me some money...

598
00:58:35,888 --> 00:58:39,892
- ...I could open my own service station.
- I can just see all the bankers...

599
00:58:40,059 --> 00:58:43,771
...falling all over to see who can give
the convict the biggest bundle.

600
00:58:43,938 --> 00:58:46,399
Hey. Ex-con.

601
00:58:46,566 --> 00:58:48,651
Why don't you give it a rest, huh?

602
00:58:49,944 --> 00:58:53,406
Well, you're the one
with all the big dreams.

603
00:58:55,700 --> 00:58:58,870
Calling Car 28, Car 2-8.
There 's a holdup at 4th and Main.

604
00:58:59,037 --> 00:59:02,248
Come on, baby, we got something
hot on the platter here.

605
00:59:09,422 --> 00:59:11,382
- You seen this before?
- What?

606
00:59:11,549 --> 00:59:15,011
Well, right before the exciting parts,
you keep squeezing my hand.

607
00:59:15,178 --> 00:59:16,387
Well, of course I do.

608
00:59:16,554 --> 00:59:19,390
I can tell when they're coming,
what with the music...

609
00:59:19,557 --> 00:59:21,684
...the way they put it together and all.

610
00:59:29,859 --> 00:59:33,029
Bonnie never told me
exactly how to keep her happy.

611
00:59:33,196 --> 00:59:36,949
She never told me one last job
wouldn't be enough.

612
00:59:37,658 --> 00:59:41,370
She just kind of let me
figure it out for myself.

613
01:00:12,276 --> 01:00:14,112
Next, please.

614
01:00:15,113 --> 01:00:17,698
I'd like to make a withdrawal.
Put it down!

615
01:00:17,907 --> 01:00:19,784
- Put it down!
- Drop it!

616
01:00:19,951 --> 01:00:23,412
Get his gun! Everybody,
get on the ground right now!

617
01:00:23,579 --> 01:00:25,832
Hey, there, you stupid?
Put your head down!

618
01:00:26,040 --> 01:00:29,752
- All right, take it easy. Take it easy.
- Ain't gonna hurt nobody!

619
01:00:30,753 --> 01:00:33,214
All right. Give me all your cash.

620
01:00:34,257 --> 01:00:35,508
Come on.

621
01:00:41,764 --> 01:00:43,266
Well, that's it?

622
01:00:44,183 --> 01:00:45,852
Yeah, that's it.

623
01:00:48,312 --> 01:00:50,523
Let's go to the vault. Come around!

624
01:00:50,690 --> 01:00:52,191
- Move. Move!
- You too. Move!

625
01:00:52,358 --> 01:00:54,235
- Move! Move!
- Easy, now.

626
01:00:54,402 --> 01:00:57,113
- There's no money in the vault.
- He's clearly lying.

627
01:00:57,280 --> 01:00:59,323
He's a banker, that's what they do.

628
01:00:59,490 --> 01:01:01,701
- Why isn't it locked?
- Well, like I said...

629
01:01:01,868 --> 01:01:04,871
...there's a depression on.
The bank's closing.

630
01:01:05,580 --> 01:01:07,999
- Everybody, in the box!
- I'm claustrophobic.

631
01:01:08,166 --> 01:01:11,377
- Well, I'm Baptist. Get in.
- Look, we won't tell.

632
01:01:11,544 --> 01:01:13,880
We won't call the cops or nothing.

633
01:01:14,714 --> 01:01:17,925
- Don't mess with Bonnie and Clyde.
- Do as they say.

634
01:01:18,092 --> 01:01:20,386
- Everybody, in the vault!
- Get in the vault!

635
01:01:20,553 --> 01:01:22,180
Get in! Get in the vault.

636
01:01:22,346 --> 01:01:25,266
- Right inside, there you go!
- Just get in, move.

637
01:01:31,522 --> 01:01:33,983
What the hell you tell them
our damn names for?

638
01:01:34,150 --> 01:01:37,403
Don't go shooting your damn gun.
Half the town probably heard.

639
01:01:37,570 --> 01:01:40,656
What you yelling for?
I got them where you told them to go.

640
01:01:40,823 --> 01:01:43,659
Because it ain't damn
"Bonnie and Clyde," all right?

641
01:01:43,826 --> 01:01:45,953
It's "Clyde and Bonnie."

642
01:02:21,530 --> 01:02:23,115
That's right.

643
01:02:33,834 --> 01:02:38,130
You look a lot more womanly
when you let your hair down.

644
01:02:38,297 --> 01:02:42,009
I followed you from work,
and the door wasn't locked.

645
01:02:43,511 --> 01:02:46,138
I've been reading your articles
in The Herald.

646
01:02:46,305 --> 01:02:48,182
You do a great job...

647
01:02:48,349 --> 01:02:53,396
...considering you're under the strictures
of reporting just the facts.

648
01:02:53,562 --> 01:02:55,856
Oh, I'm not criticizing. I just ....

649
01:02:56,023 --> 01:02:59,986
What with all the foreclosures
and woes of the stock market...

650
01:03:00,152 --> 01:03:05,366
...seems like people could stand
a little less black-and-white truth...

651
01:03:05,533 --> 01:03:10,329
...and a skosh more being entertained.

652
01:03:10,705 --> 01:03:13,040
What are you doing here?

653
01:03:13,666 --> 01:03:15,626
I'm just a fan.

654
01:03:16,085 --> 01:03:19,797
Oh, I gotta say, I was surprised
when I found out P.J. was a woman.

655
01:03:20,298 --> 01:03:23,676
You always called yourself P.J.?
Or was that your boss's idea...

656
01:03:23,843 --> 01:03:27,305
...to stop your readers from finding out
you were a Patricia?

657
01:03:27,680 --> 01:03:31,475
Maybe it's me, but seems like things
are moving forward for our gender.

658
01:03:31,642 --> 01:03:35,855
What with that Amelia Earhart
fixing to fly across the Atlantic...

659
01:03:36,063 --> 01:03:39,483
...and you in the newsroom
writing about crime...

660
01:03:40,109 --> 01:03:43,988
...and me out there committing them.

661
01:03:46,157 --> 01:03:48,075
I couldn't help but notice...

662
01:03:49,910 --> 01:03:53,205
...you only put Clyde's name down.

663
01:03:55,708 --> 01:04:00,212
Nice of you to mention me
only as "female companion."

664
01:04:00,379 --> 01:04:01,547
Wasn't my idea.

665
01:04:01,881 --> 01:04:05,760
My editor said if a girl was involved
in an armed robbery, it had to be...

666
01:04:05,926 --> 01:04:08,846
- ...her man making her do it.
- Really?

667
01:04:10,139 --> 01:04:11,932
Imagine that.

668
01:04:16,604 --> 01:04:18,647
Would you please
get out of my house?

669
01:04:22,485 --> 01:04:25,071
Oh, yeah, sure. Sorry.

670
01:04:27,740 --> 01:04:30,743
Oh, goodness, P.J.,
I never introduced myself.

671
01:04:31,619 --> 01:04:33,371
I'm Bonnie Parker.

672
01:04:33,579 --> 01:04:37,666
A la Bonnie and Clyde.

673
01:04:55,142 --> 01:04:59,730
I'm busy. Looks like you got something
going on in that fine-looking head...

674
01:04:59,897 --> 01:05:03,901
You wanted my story twice as interesting,
but out out the interesting part.

675
01:05:04,068 --> 01:05:06,904
A woman used a shotgun
in a strong-arm robbery...

676
01:05:07,071 --> 01:05:11,075
...and I get a quarter of a column on
page 12 and I can't even use her name?

677
01:05:11,242 --> 01:05:14,161
- So, what do you want from me?
- Let me follow the story.

678
01:05:14,328 --> 01:05:17,623
Write it the way I want
or I'll go find a paper that will.

679
01:05:17,832 --> 01:05:19,667
Maybe you'd better start finding...

680
01:05:19,834 --> 01:05:23,337
...because a skirt trying to act like
she isn't, that I don't need.

681
01:05:34,765 --> 01:05:38,060
You know, when you keep putting guns
in people 's faces...

682
01:05:38,227 --> 01:05:40,896
...the gods tend to frown
on such behavior...

683
01:05:41,063 --> 01:05:43,941
...and all sorts of things can go awry.

684
01:05:44,191 --> 01:05:47,903
- Clyde? You ran us out of gas.
- Gauge said it was a quarter full.

685
01:05:48,112 --> 01:05:50,156
Well, laws will be on us.

686
01:05:51,240 --> 01:05:52,658
Damn it.

687
01:05:52,825 --> 01:05:55,494
All right, let's go. Come on.

688
01:05:56,162 --> 01:05:59,915
Come on, run. Come on. Let's go.

689
01:06:20,060 --> 01:06:21,187
Go!

690
01:06:27,318 --> 01:06:29,987
- Do you know where we're going?
- Not at the moment.

691
01:06:30,196 --> 01:06:35,159
- All this for $46 in the rm.
- $46.32, baby.

692
01:06:51,383 --> 01:06:53,761
Get down. Get down.

693
01:06:59,767 --> 01:07:01,810
- Did you get them, Clyde?
- Ain't trying.

694
01:07:01,977 --> 01:07:04,605
I ain't killing laws. No future in that.

695
01:07:04,813 --> 01:07:08,442
Y'all better give up!
Come out with your hands up!

696
01:07:10,319 --> 01:07:11,570
Do we give up, Clyde?

697
01:07:12,530 --> 01:07:15,199
If I do, I'm 20 years in jail.

698
01:07:18,827 --> 01:07:22,581
Then you go. You go. Run. Run.

699
01:07:22,748 --> 01:07:25,709
- I ain't gonna leave you, Bonnie.
- I ain't got a record.

700
01:07:25,876 --> 01:07:28,671
They'll throw me in jail.
I'll talk my way out.

701
01:07:28,879 --> 01:07:30,714
Give it up, Barrow!

702
01:07:31,882 --> 01:07:36,637
- You told those bank clerks your name.
- Well, that was clear across the state.

703
01:07:36,804 --> 01:07:39,598
Nobody put my damn name
in the paper anyway.

704
01:08:04,873 --> 01:08:07,501
All right, ma'am, on your feet.

705
01:08:08,294 --> 01:08:09,753
Let's go.

706
01:08:17,428 --> 01:08:21,056
Promise to tell the truth,
the whole truth and nothing but the truth?

707
01:08:21,223 --> 01:08:22,641
I do.

708
01:08:23,017 --> 01:08:27,354
Funny, when you're an outlaw,
you tell so many lies...

709
01:08:27,521 --> 01:08:30,691
...after a while, you don't know
what's a lie and what isn't.

710
01:08:31,734 --> 01:08:35,029
And Bonnie, she could really
spin e story.

711
01:08:36,155 --> 01:08:41,660
I must admit,
I fell under the sway of Clyde Barrow.

712
01:08:42,578 --> 01:08:47,708
Believed like... Like a schoolgirl,
I could right what was wrong in him.

713
01:08:48,500 --> 01:08:52,504
And when the criming started,
I couldn't stop it.

714
01:08:54,256 --> 01:08:59,386
I tried to get away,
but Clyde wouldn't let me.

715
01:09:00,721 --> 01:09:05,184
He wouldn't sleep till he put
a out of leather between my lips...

716
01:09:06,435 --> 01:09:10,397
...and bound me up in rope
in nothing but my underclothes.

717
01:09:12,316 --> 01:09:17,071
And this limp of mine.
Clyde tied me up so tight...

718
01:09:17,321 --> 01:09:20,699
...I lost circulation all the way
from my ankle to my thigh.

719
01:09:24,078 --> 01:09:26,830
Bondage, it's horrible.

720
01:09:28,248 --> 01:09:30,459
Truly God-awful horrible.

721
01:09:31,293 --> 01:09:33,629
Almost more than a woman can bear.

722
01:09:34,672 --> 01:09:39,468
And when Clyde wanted his way with me,
there wasn't much I could do.

723
01:09:39,760 --> 01:09:44,932
I only weigh 106 pounds
and Clyde was so strong.

724
01:09:45,432 --> 01:09:49,812
And l... Forgive me, Jesus.

725
01:09:50,729 --> 01:09:52,731
... I was so weak.

726
01:09:53,148 --> 01:09:57,736
What me and Bonnie done,
those we stole from and the laws...

727
01:09:57,986 --> 01:10:03,367
...they'd probably tell things different.
Hell, even Bonnie, sure she would too.

728
01:10:03,575 --> 01:10:05,703
Bonnie 'd surely tell it with more flair.

729
01:10:13,836 --> 01:10:16,505
Take some water, ma'am.
Take some water.

730
01:10:17,464 --> 01:10:18,882
Thank you.

731
01:10:29,351 --> 01:10:33,147
I can't tell you how good it is
to see you out of that godforsaken hole.

732
01:10:33,313 --> 01:10:35,858
Jail is no place for a lady.

733
01:10:36,024 --> 01:10:38,902
- Like the new 'do.
- And I was fond of your performance.

734
01:10:40,195 --> 01:10:44,616
- Haven't seen your byline in a while, P.J.
- Yeah, well, things are tough all over.

735
01:10:46,118 --> 01:10:48,871
- What was she talking about?
- She's a reporter.

736
01:10:49,037 --> 01:10:53,250
- Gotta talk about something.
- Gee, you looked good, Bonnie.

737
01:10:53,459 --> 01:10:57,504
I picked up that little old chest of yours.
It's right where you said it was.

738
01:10:57,671 --> 01:11:00,674
So, what do you want to do?

739
01:11:00,841 --> 01:11:01,967
Go to a show?

740
01:11:03,135 --> 01:11:06,013
Maybe buy a new dress?
I got a little money saved.

741
01:11:07,222 --> 01:11:11,518
Gr, you're worn out. You just want
to go home and do each ether's nails?

742
01:11:11,727 --> 01:11:14,521
- Afraid I'm not going home, Mama.
- What?

743
01:11:15,272 --> 01:11:18,442
Some of what I said in that courtroom...

744
01:11:20,694 --> 01:11:21,987
...it wasn't true.

745
01:11:23,447 --> 01:11:26,074
- Clyde never took me, Mama.
- Of course he did.

746
01:11:26,241 --> 01:11:30,454
You've been telling me he did since
the first time I sat with you in your cell.

747
01:11:31,914 --> 01:11:34,249
You're saying he didn't take you?

748
01:11:35,834 --> 01:11:39,963
Everything you've been telling me,
everything you said before that judge...

749
01:11:41,965 --> 01:11:44,092
- ...that was all just an act.
- Mama.

750
01:11:54,686 --> 01:11:56,063
I'm sorry, Mama.

751
01:12:02,110 --> 01:12:04,154
- Bonnie.
- Yeah?

752
01:12:05,906 --> 01:12:10,160
- You'll come see me, won't you?
- You know I will, Mama.

753
01:12:37,729 --> 01:12:41,567
So give me the corrected story
first thing in the morning.

754
01:12:41,775 --> 01:12:44,236
We'll give you three-quarters
of page two...

755
01:12:44,444 --> 01:12:47,573
...800-, 900 words,
nothing more, nothing less.

756
01:12:47,823 --> 01:12:51,493
So, what makes you think
I'm gonna give you your job back?

757
01:12:51,660 --> 01:12:54,037
You don't want
to be stuck at the station...

758
01:12:54,204 --> 01:12:58,125
...on the biggest story that's about
to start racing down the tracks.

759
01:12:58,584 --> 01:12:59,626
Who's that?

760
01:12:59,793 --> 01:13:02,004
She sold the Kaufman County
Grand Jury...

761
01:13:02,170 --> 01:13:05,340
...the biggest load I ever saw
shoveled down anyone's throat.

762
01:13:05,507 --> 01:13:08,135
You're going to rehire me
to write about her.

763
01:13:08,468 --> 01:13:10,012
Her name's Bonnie Parker.

764
01:13:10,178 --> 01:13:13,640
She's got more personality than
nine movie stars put together.

765
01:13:14,016 --> 01:13:18,437
She's romantically linked with a
rebellious, disenfranchised son of Texas.

766
01:13:18,604 --> 01:13:22,441
Unless I'm wrong, the two of them
are about to embark on a crime spree...

767
01:13:22,608 --> 01:13:26,612
...with lots of violence, glamour
and car chases.

768
01:13:26,778 --> 01:13:29,364
And it isn't just the man
shooting the guns.

769
01:13:30,449 --> 01:13:32,200
So you're saying there's sex too.

770
01:13:59,394 --> 01:14:00,896
Come on, Barrow.

771
01:14:11,323 --> 01:14:14,368
There's the dreadful girl's mother.

772
01:14:17,204 --> 01:14:20,457
- Just awful, shameful.
- It is.

773
01:14:58,370 --> 01:15:03,250
- Clyde Chestnut, what the hell?
- Supposed to be in prison, big gorilla.

774
01:15:03,417 --> 01:15:06,169
Yeah, warden made the mistake
of making me a trustee.

775
01:15:06,336 --> 01:15:09,506
- I made the mistake of busting out.
- Mistake of busting out?

776
01:15:10,340 --> 01:15:14,219
I'm gonna spend the rest of the
weekend with this lovely thing here...

777
01:15:14,386 --> 01:15:16,888
...and then I'm gonna
turn myself back in.

778
01:15:17,097 --> 01:15:20,892
- Hearing a lot about you, Clyde Chestnut.
- Clyde Chestnut?

779
01:15:21,101 --> 01:15:23,812
- He told me it was Champion.
- Champion?

780
01:15:23,979 --> 01:15:26,440
Trying to impress me, I guess.

781
01:15:26,606 --> 01:15:29,443
I tried my best to do right by her.

782
01:15:30,444 --> 01:15:32,571
Well, don't beat yourself up.

783
01:15:32,779 --> 01:15:35,323
They're gonna go
the way they're gonna go...

784
01:15:35,490 --> 01:15:37,951
...pretty much no matter what we do.

785
01:15:39,578 --> 01:15:41,121
Yeah, I guess.

786
01:15:41,496 --> 01:15:45,250
Hey, Blanche, you mind
grabbing us a beer?

787
01:15:45,417 --> 01:15:46,877
All right.

788
01:15:48,628 --> 01:15:50,839
We're the luckiest women
in the world, huh?

789
01:15:51,214 --> 01:15:53,341
You done good, boy.

790
01:15:54,634 --> 01:15:58,180
Anybody ever turn themselves
back into Huntsville, Marvin?

791
01:15:58,472 --> 01:16:00,390
How the hell should I know?

792
01:16:00,682 --> 01:16:03,810
I mean, Blanche's father's a preacher.

793
01:16:03,977 --> 01:16:07,689
And she said she won't part
her sweet haunches till I marry her.

794
01:16:07,856 --> 01:16:10,776
Her father won't marry us
till I do the rest of my time.

795
01:16:10,942 --> 01:16:13,153
Right. I think I could launch myself...

796
01:16:13,320 --> 01:16:15,697
...clear to the moon.
I'll tell you one thing.

797
01:16:15,864 --> 01:16:19,618
Preacher's daughter or not,
she is one fine load of naughty.

798
01:16:19,785 --> 01:16:23,538
Well, not that that's everything.

799
01:16:24,081 --> 01:16:25,665
Right?

800
01:16:29,753 --> 01:16:33,548
- What's Mom so pissy about?
- She's always pissy.

801
01:16:33,715 --> 01:16:36,426
- She took the money I gave her.
- We need the money.

802
01:16:36,593 --> 01:16:39,137
It ain't the criming that's got her goat.

803
01:16:39,638 --> 01:16:42,307
Should've hit you boys more.

804
01:16:42,766 --> 01:16:44,935
She doesn't like Bonnie, does she?

805
01:16:45,102 --> 01:16:49,523
She doesn't like
that she's married not to you.

806
01:16:52,651 --> 01:16:55,821
Yeah, should've hit him more.

807
01:16:57,322 --> 01:17:01,993
You know, Bonnie'd get divorced
if she could...

808
01:17:03,245 --> 01:17:08,083
...but just kind of a legal proceeding,
you know, and legal and us ....

809
01:17:08,416 --> 01:17:11,628
Doesn't mean she couldn't take off
Roy Thornton's ring.

810
01:17:13,255 --> 01:17:16,675
It's a nice piece of jewelry, Mom.
Bonnie likes jewelry.

811
01:17:16,842 --> 01:17:20,887
And fine clothes and expensive shoes
and getting famous.

812
01:17:21,429 --> 01:17:24,474
I'm just wondering how much
she really likes you.

813
01:17:24,724 --> 01:17:26,309
Oh, she likes me fine.

814
01:17:29,855 --> 01:17:34,025
I was making a record. Remember
what I used to call you, Clyde?

815
01:17:34,192 --> 01:17:35,986
Your "little ray of sunshine."

816
01:17:36,528 --> 01:17:39,281
Wrote down where we gathered,
here at Perkins' barn.

817
01:17:39,447 --> 01:17:42,742
What we ate, what we drank,
who was here.

818
01:17:42,909 --> 01:17:48,165
Know I'm only gonna be seeing you
here and there from here on out...

819
01:17:48,331 --> 01:17:52,419
...and I don't want to forget
any of the here and theres.

820
01:17:54,671 --> 01:17:56,590
I love you, Mom.

821
01:19:00,195 --> 01:19:05,325
The robbery in Hillsboro, right from
the get-go, just felt different.

822
01:19:06,076 --> 01:19:09,704
Jesus, Clyde,
you're making me nervous.

823
01:19:09,955 --> 01:19:12,040
I could've stopped it.

824
01:19:12,457 --> 01:19:14,042
I should've.

825
01:19:14,417 --> 01:19:16,127
Because after tonight...

826
01:19:17,462 --> 01:19:20,090
...nothing was ever
gonna be the same.

827
01:19:20,674 --> 01:19:23,385
My old buddy Fults
wasn't two weeks out of jail...

828
01:19:23,551 --> 01:19:27,347
...before I got him back doing what
landed him there in the first place.

829
01:19:27,514 --> 01:19:28,807
Come on.

830
01:19:33,311 --> 01:19:36,606
- Please don't hurt me.
- You do what we say...

831
01:19:36,773 --> 01:19:40,568
...just be another good story
to tell your buddies at the Moose Lodge.

832
01:19:50,870 --> 01:19:55,500
Hang on a second. Hey.
This doesn't seem right.

833
01:19:56,001 --> 01:20:00,422
- What are you talking about?
- Like this might not be the right job.

834
01:20:00,630 --> 01:20:04,884
- Don't even. We're already doing the job.
- We need money to eat tomorrow.

835
01:20:05,051 --> 01:20:08,430
- If you hadn't spent so much on clothes...
- I can't go back...

836
01:20:08,596 --> 01:20:11,558
You guys wanna argue
about shopping, be my guest.

837
01:20:11,725 --> 01:20:14,185
But I'm doing the damn job.

838
01:20:15,937 --> 01:20:18,606
Come on. Come on.

839
01:20:21,693 --> 01:20:23,153
Faster.

840
01:20:27,824 --> 01:20:29,367
Come on, open it.

841
01:20:45,925 --> 01:20:47,218
Come on.

842
01:20:55,810 --> 01:20:57,479
Hear that?

843
01:21:00,065 --> 01:21:04,277
Just the cash.
Put it in the purse. Come on.

844
01:21:04,861 --> 01:21:06,988
A little faster.

845
01:21:10,241 --> 01:21:11,701
Come on.

846
01:21:12,077 --> 01:21:15,205
- All right, let's go.
- Come on.

847
01:21:24,422 --> 01:21:27,425
- What y'all gonna do with me?
- Nothing.

848
01:21:27,592 --> 01:21:31,096
Go upstairs, stay there till the sun
comes up. You're done with us.

849
01:22:01,751 --> 01:22:04,254
Despite all the things we done...

850
01:22:04,421 --> 01:22:08,216
...bullets flying north, south,
east and west...

851
01:22:08,425 --> 01:22:10,677
...no one had been killed before.

852
01:22:10,844 --> 01:22:14,222
A few here and there
may have collected some lead...

853
01:22:14,431 --> 01:22:16,641
...but no one had been killed.

854
01:22:33,741 --> 01:22:35,660
Miss Lane, I'm Captain Grace.

855
01:22:35,827 --> 01:22:38,496
- Anything we can help you sort out?
- Seems clear.

856
01:22:38,663 --> 01:22:42,125
I was hoping you could tell me
the ABC's of it in your own words.

857
01:22:42,292 --> 01:22:45,336
Well, plates matched a vehicle
they stole in Topeka.

858
01:22:45,503 --> 01:22:49,132
Looks like they got money and some
jewels from the safe here and ran.

859
01:22:49,299 --> 01:22:52,552
Not before obliterating Mr. Bucher,
apparently for the thrill.

860
01:22:52,802 --> 01:22:55,889
All fingers seem to be pointing
at who as the triggerman?

861
01:22:56,097 --> 01:22:57,891
Clyde Barrow.

862
01:22:58,391 --> 01:23:01,936
I just spoke to the widow.
Told me she could see the whole thing...

863
01:23:02,270 --> 01:23:05,815
...from her bedroom window.
I showed her the picture of Clyde.

864
01:23:05,982 --> 01:23:08,818
She said he couldn't have
possibly pulled the trigger.

865
01:23:09,027 --> 01:23:13,198
All I know is those maggots came to steal
money, now an innocent man's dead.

866
01:23:13,364 --> 01:23:17,243
Now, I'd appreciate it if you'd get
your smart ass off my crime site.

867
01:23:28,880 --> 01:23:31,674
Nobody meant for it to happen, Bon.

868
01:23:32,675 --> 01:23:35,094
The press could've hung us worse.

869
01:23:36,971 --> 01:23:38,348
You shouldn't be drinking.

870
01:23:47,190 --> 01:23:49,901
I'm a horrible person, Clyde.

871
01:23:51,152 --> 01:23:52,987
That poor man's dead...

872
01:23:54,030 --> 01:23:57,659
...and I'm all bent because the paper
used my stupid sophomore photo.

873
01:23:57,825 --> 01:24:00,578
- You're not a horrible person.
- Yeah.

874
01:24:00,745 --> 01:24:04,207
- Yeah, I am.
- You're just honest.

875
01:24:04,415 --> 01:24:09,045
Gonna get out of town before sunup.
Gonna be all right while I jack us a ride?

876
01:24:09,587 --> 01:24:10,838
Yeah.

877
01:24:16,261 --> 01:24:17,887
Cly?

878
01:24:20,807 --> 01:24:24,102
- You really think I don't look stupid?
- Not at all.

879
01:24:24,727 --> 01:24:27,605
But you definitely look better in person.

880
01:24:44,038 --> 01:24:48,793
"Bonnie and Clyde."

881
01:25:37,133 --> 01:25:41,971
"Bonnie and Clyde."

882
01:26:13,836 --> 01:26:16,756
You know what
I've been thinking, Clyde?

883
01:26:16,923 --> 01:26:19,967
I think we should do bigger jobs.

884
01:26:21,803 --> 01:26:24,263
Maybe we shouldn't do any more jobs.

885
01:26:24,972 --> 01:26:27,141
Well, fine...

886
01:26:28,017 --> 01:26:30,561
...but if we're gonna,
they ought to be big ones.

887
01:26:30,728 --> 01:26:34,440
Aren't gonna get that lake house of yours
doing five-and-dime stickups.

888
01:26:34,607 --> 01:26:38,069
And stuff can go wrong
just as likely doing them.

889
01:26:38,236 --> 01:26:41,656
Don't feel comfortable doing bigger jobs
just the two of us.

890
01:26:42,699 --> 01:26:44,951
Maybe we should hook back up
with Fults.

891
01:26:45,118 --> 01:26:47,245
What, so he can gun down
some poor SOB...

892
01:26:47,412 --> 01:26:50,123
...who done nothing wrong
whatsoever?

893
01:26:50,289 --> 01:26:53,459
Well, what about your brother?
He's done his time, hasn't he?

894
01:26:53,626 --> 01:26:56,212
Yeah, and he ain't looking
to do any more.

895
01:26:57,213 --> 01:26:59,632
I ain't getting Buck involved in this.

896
01:27:00,633 --> 01:27:02,009
Well, somebody else, then.

897
01:27:02,176 --> 01:27:04,679
Gonna pull bigger jobs,
we need bigger guns too.

898
01:27:04,846 --> 01:27:08,057
Well, then somebody else
and bigger guns.

899
01:27:09,559 --> 01:27:13,980
Weren't you just crying about
that poor son of a bitch in the p.j.'s'?

900
01:27:14,147 --> 01:27:17,024
For Pete's sake, Clyde,
I'm not saying we use them.

901
01:27:17,191 --> 01:27:19,610
If we pull big guns on people...

902
01:27:19,777 --> 01:27:23,197
...they're gonna do
exactly what we tell them to.

903
01:27:25,491 --> 01:27:27,452
All right, look here.

904
01:27:27,952 --> 01:27:31,539
Just so you know, who's in the gang...

905
01:27:31,706 --> 01:27:34,959
...what we do,
what kind of guns we use...

906
01:27:35,126 --> 01:27:40,590
...or if we go and join a damn monastery,
it's all up to me.

907
01:27:41,340 --> 01:27:43,509
I make the decisions.

908
01:27:44,093 --> 01:27:45,720
All right?

909
01:27:46,387 --> 01:27:49,682
Fine. Just a thought.

910
01:27:51,225 --> 01:27:53,436
Sorry I had one.

911
01:28:14,332 --> 01:28:16,167
Come on, let's go.

912
01:28:54,705 --> 01:28:57,250
- Barrow?
- Miss me?

913
01:28:57,750 --> 01:29:01,587
- Where'd you get the suit?
- Just picked it up from a tailor.

914
01:29:02,213 --> 01:29:03,256
Damn crazy.

915
01:29:14,559 --> 01:29:17,019
... three, four, five, six, seven, eight...

916
01:29:22,525 --> 01:29:25,236
Herman?
We got one too many convicts.

917
01:29:25,403 --> 01:29:28,489
Now you're about to have one too few.
Don't move.

918
01:29:38,541 --> 01:29:41,127
Gonna shoot me, are you, Barrow?

919
01:29:48,342 --> 01:29:50,136
Go! Go!

920
01:29:51,095 --> 01:29:52,471
Outrun them.

921
01:30:01,188 --> 01:30:03,274
Move around, other side.

922
01:30:06,068 --> 01:30:07,695
Through here.

923
01:30:09,947 --> 01:30:12,033
They're heading for the road.

924
01:30:18,122 --> 01:30:19,540
Down, get down!

925
01:30:25,129 --> 01:30:29,926
- Bonnie, Ray. Ray, Bonnie.
- Like your choice of weapons, Bonnie.

926
01:30:50,404 --> 01:30:51,822
It's the warden.

927
01:30:51,989 --> 01:30:54,033
- Watch this.
- Clyde.

928
01:30:54,241 --> 01:30:56,994
- What are they doing?
- They're busting out.

929
01:31:00,331 --> 01:31:02,458
- Clyde, you really need to?
- Yup.

930
01:31:02,959 --> 01:31:04,001
Barrow.

931
01:31:06,295 --> 01:31:07,421
Oh, God.

932
01:31:40,746 --> 01:31:44,125
Ma'am. I'm here to see
Colonel Simmons.

933
01:31:44,291 --> 01:31:47,545
- I'll let him know you're both here.
- Thanks.

934
01:31:59,682 --> 01:32:01,684
You're Frank Hamer.

935
01:32:03,936 --> 01:32:08,774
I'm Ted Hinton,
deputy of the Dallas P.D.

936
01:32:10,234 --> 01:32:12,236
I know Bonnie.

937
01:32:12,403 --> 01:32:16,365
- I know both her and Clyde by sight.
- I know who you are.

938
01:32:17,783 --> 01:32:20,119
And I know what you know.

939
01:32:22,997 --> 01:32:26,709
They share a posse, Frank,
but I would put them on the spot...

940
01:32:26,876 --> 01:32:30,588
...make sure it's them,
and shoot everybody in sight.

941
01:32:30,755 --> 01:32:33,090
That's about the run of it.

942
01:32:33,257 --> 01:32:35,843
- Any questions?
- Just one.

943
01:32:36,802 --> 01:32:39,388
Hope I'm not hearing the idea
is to shoot first...

944
01:32:39,555 --> 01:32:43,225
...and ask them to put their hands up
when they're too dead to do it.

945
01:32:43,392 --> 01:32:44,643
Before she met Barrow...

946
01:32:44,810 --> 01:32:48,314
...Bonnie Parker was a good girl
from a good family.

947
01:32:48,481 --> 01:32:51,984
Yeah, well, bringing them to trial
would be best in any case.

948
01:32:52,151 --> 01:32:54,820
If you collar Barrow,
it wouldn't displease me.

949
01:32:54,987 --> 01:32:58,824
- We'd love having him back.
- Not a question of if, just when.

950
01:32:58,991 --> 01:33:01,077
Let's keep the press out of this.

951
01:33:01,243 --> 01:33:05,498
If Barrow finds out we're on their trail,
it'll just make our job a lot harder.

952
01:33:07,792 --> 01:33:11,253
Anything you can tell me
from Barrow's time here...

953
01:33:11,420 --> 01:33:15,591
...that might help in tracking him?
Distinguishing characteristics or the like?

954
01:33:15,758 --> 01:33:19,303
He just might be limping
on his left side.

955
01:33:22,598 --> 01:33:27,019
Barrow paid the guy he busted out
to hack that little piggy off.

956
01:33:37,988 --> 01:33:41,242
Always heard legends seemed smaller
when you met them.

957
01:33:42,576 --> 01:33:45,412
Was wondering if I could buy you dinner
on the Herald.

958
01:33:45,579 --> 01:33:48,541
- Would like to do a full-on feature on you.
- The Herald?

959
01:33:50,835 --> 01:33:52,128
You must be P.J. Lane.

960
01:33:53,462 --> 01:33:55,881
I read some of your pieces, Miss Lane.

961
01:33:56,924 --> 01:33:59,301
- You ought to be writing fiction.
- How's that?

962
01:33:59,468 --> 01:34:02,471
It's inventive now you made
law enforcement the bad guy...

963
01:34:02,638 --> 01:34:05,141
...for insinuating Barrow
had something to do...

964
01:34:05,307 --> 01:34:07,726
...with the murder of that store owner.

965
01:34:07,893 --> 01:34:10,312
What would dinner on you get me?

966
01:34:10,479 --> 01:34:14,400
Keep you from having to read the same
baloney written about you before.

967
01:34:14,567 --> 01:34:16,110
About being able to hear shots...

968
01:34:16,277 --> 01:34:18,737
...before they're
fired and gunning down 56 outlaws.

969
01:34:19,613 --> 01:34:21,949
Fifty-seven, Miss Lane.

970
01:34:22,825 --> 01:34:23,868
Have a good one.

971
01:34:24,034 --> 01:34:26,579
Come on.
Going to write about you either way.

972
01:34:26,745 --> 01:34:30,708
At least tell me what about Bonnie
and Clyde brought you out of retirement.

973
01:34:31,542 --> 01:34:32,793
It was the publicity.

974
01:35:05,075 --> 01:35:06,952
- Stop! Police!
- You with the bag!

975
01:35:20,883 --> 01:35:22,426
Get in.

976
01:35:24,470 --> 01:35:25,596
Stop!

977
01:35:31,101 --> 01:35:34,647
I think you picked the right bank
to spring, Clyde.

978
01:35:58,420 --> 01:36:00,589
You smoke, Bonnie Parker?

979
01:36:01,507 --> 01:36:04,677
Nope. I was raised Christian.

980
01:36:13,227 --> 01:36:15,145
You dropped something.

981
01:36:21,193 --> 01:36:25,281
Do yourself a favor, Ray.
Grab a cold bath.

982
01:36:32,121 --> 01:36:33,372
What's for breakfast?

983
01:36:34,081 --> 01:36:37,459
Lady at the bakery said
these are best damn doughnuts ever.

984
01:36:37,626 --> 01:36:39,586
- Great.
- I got you something else too.

985
01:36:39,753 --> 01:36:40,796
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

986
01:36:40,963 --> 01:36:42,423
What?

987
01:36:43,299 --> 01:36:46,677
Kodak Folding Autographic, all right?

988
01:36:46,844 --> 01:36:51,473
It's got focusable lenses,
eight pictures per roll, the whole deal.

989
01:36:51,640 --> 01:36:55,894
Figure it's time we do something about
that old sophomore photo of yours, huh?

990
01:36:58,063 --> 01:37:03,027
Yeah. So I wanna shoot you down there,
get you on some rocks.

991
01:37:03,193 --> 01:37:04,445
- Clyde.
- Clump of trees.

992
01:37:04,611 --> 01:37:07,865
- We aren't shooting the photos today.
- Why not?

993
01:37:08,032 --> 01:37:11,702
Problem with that photo, I didn't know
they were taking them that day.

994
01:37:11,869 --> 01:37:15,205
Girl's gotta get clothes,
tailoring to get the fit.

995
01:37:15,372 --> 01:37:18,208
You're asking for trouble
if you don't get a makeover.

996
01:37:18,375 --> 01:37:21,628
- What's a makeover?
- You could stand some new dude.

997
01:37:21,795 --> 01:37:24,381
Not to mention a cut.

998
01:37:24,840 --> 01:37:30,220
- Your hair is strictly '20s.
- Hey there. You be nice.

999
01:38:29,154 --> 01:38:31,323
Been in there forever. My turn for a dip.

1000
01:38:33,951 --> 01:38:35,953
Unless you want to double dip.

1001
01:38:37,621 --> 01:38:40,749
You got water in those ears?
I'm talking to you.

1002
01:38:42,042 --> 01:38:43,877
You all right, Clyde?

1003
01:38:47,589 --> 01:38:49,425
We need to stop.

1004
01:38:50,175 --> 01:38:51,218
What?

1005
01:38:52,886 --> 01:38:57,099
Did you see this?

1006
01:38:57,266 --> 01:39:01,395
- You see who they hired to hunt us?
- Looks like he's seen better days.

1007
01:39:01,562 --> 01:39:06,483
Yeah. You know,
I met him back at the blacksmith shop.

1008
01:39:07,526 --> 01:39:12,406
I knew it was a sign
that we needed to stop all this.

1009
01:39:13,031 --> 01:39:15,200
Frank Hamer's
the meanest son of a bitch.

1010
01:39:15,367 --> 01:39:19,496
I know it sounds crazy,
but I seen something.

1011
01:39:19,663 --> 01:39:20,831
It wasn't good at all.

1012
01:39:20,998 --> 01:39:23,167
This is about one of those things
you see?

1013
01:39:23,333 --> 01:39:25,252
- You don't understand.
- I understand.

1014
01:39:25,419 --> 01:39:29,089
Keep talking like that, they'll put you
in a place worse than prison.

1015
01:39:29,256 --> 01:39:31,467
We need to get out while we can,
Bonnie.

1016
01:39:32,134 --> 01:39:35,220
Forget about Ray and robbing banks.

1017
01:39:35,429 --> 01:39:37,931
- All of it.
- And get into what, missionary work?

1018
01:39:38,140 --> 01:39:40,559
And if I have a dream...

1019
01:39:40,726 --> 01:39:43,687
...about a purple nine-eyed demon
under our bed...

1020
01:39:43,896 --> 01:39:46,231
...should we give up sleeping together?

1021
01:39:47,024 --> 01:39:50,027
- You think I'm kidding around here, huh?
- No.

1022
01:39:50,194 --> 01:39:52,404
We just risked our necks
to bust Ray out...

1023
01:39:52,571 --> 01:39:56,158
...so that we could get done
what we both agreed we were gonna do.

1024
01:39:56,325 --> 01:39:59,369
- So we could get what we both wanted.
- Yeah?

1025
01:39:59,536 --> 01:40:01,705
Well, maybe I already got
what I wanted.

1026
01:40:01,872 --> 01:40:06,084
And if I say it's time to shut it down,
it's time to shut it down, all right?

1027
01:40:06,251 --> 01:40:09,129
- Well, maybe it is.
- Maybe it is.

1028
01:40:27,064 --> 01:40:28,649
Bonnie?

1029
01:40:29,358 --> 01:40:30,817
I'm fine, Clyde.

1030
01:40:30,984 --> 01:40:33,737
Yeah? It's almost midnight.
You gonna come to bed?

1031
01:40:37,032 --> 01:40:39,451
When I'm done bathing.

1032
01:41:14,194 --> 01:41:16,572
Since when you smoking?

1033
01:41:20,784 --> 01:41:22,828
What's going on, Bon?

1034
01:41:25,455 --> 01:41:28,208
You had some premonition
or something.

1035
01:41:29,376 --> 01:41:32,087
I guess I gotta try and understand that.

1036
01:41:33,046 --> 01:41:36,133
But I knew there were gonna be
lawmen after us.

1037
01:41:36,341 --> 01:41:42,097
And whatever this Frank Hamer is to you,
he's just another one to me.

1038
01:41:42,723 --> 01:41:46,143
And I gotta tell you,
what I see looking forward...

1039
01:41:46,351 --> 01:41:48,937
...isn't dark and foreboding at all.

1040
01:41:49,813 --> 01:41:55,068
I see the two of us waking up one day
with all this behind us...

1041
01:41:55,569 --> 01:41:58,697
...with everything we ever dreamed of.

1042
01:42:01,074 --> 01:42:06,580
Now, maybe the road we're taking
to get to dreamland isn't the greatest.

1043
01:42:07,748 --> 01:42:09,541
But it's the road that called us.

1044
01:42:10,083 --> 01:42:15,839
And if you're demanding
we stop this thing we're doing...

1045
01:42:16,715 --> 01:42:18,634
...then I don't know.

1046
01:42:20,552 --> 01:42:24,848
Maybe I'm gonna have to find some other
way to get where I'm supposed to be.

1047
01:42:32,898 --> 01:42:35,233
You ain't going nowhere.

1048
01:43:14,314 --> 01:43:18,235
Hey, not like I break the lens or anything.
Snap a couple of me and Bonnie.

1049
01:43:20,028 --> 01:43:21,655
All right.

1050
01:43:27,953 --> 01:43:30,330
Get more of a close-up.
You're way back there.

1051
01:43:30,497 --> 01:43:32,582
You can hardly see our smiles.

1052
01:43:35,544 --> 01:43:36,712
- Go ahead.
- What?

1053
01:43:37,921 --> 01:43:40,799
- That'll make you look mean.
- Not to mention sexy.

1054
01:43:42,426 --> 01:43:45,220
Hey, Ray,
you got some tobacco on your lip.

1055
01:43:45,387 --> 01:43:47,514
Yeah, let me see that.

1056
01:43:47,681 --> 01:43:49,141
- I get it?
- Right there.

1057
01:43:50,308 --> 01:43:52,185
Damn.

1058
01:43:53,729 --> 01:43:56,231
Come here.
Got a little something for you.

1059
01:43:56,398 --> 01:43:58,400
Snap one like this first.

1060
01:43:58,608 --> 01:43:59,901
- All right.
- Oh, wait.

1061
01:44:00,068 --> 01:44:01,862
Make it even better right here.

1062
01:44:08,702 --> 01:44:10,746
Make it look mean. Come on.

1063
01:44:52,245 --> 01:44:56,291
Was excited to near Colonel Simmons
got you on board, Captain Hamer.

1064
01:44:56,458 --> 01:45:01,046
We can use all the help we can get.
We narrowed it down to a five-state area.

1065
01:45:02,297 --> 01:45:06,885
Barrow's only committed a couple
of his crimes outside of here, Texas.

1066
01:45:07,052 --> 01:45:11,348
You can tell by the density on the map
where he's done most of his damage.

1067
01:45:11,515 --> 01:45:14,768
We've got all the information
on the crimes in this journal...

1068
01:45:14,935 --> 01:45:16,728
...every detail you could imagine.

1069
01:45:16,895 --> 01:45:19,898
We've recovered some of the clothes.

1070
01:45:20,398 --> 01:45:22,484
You can take a look at them
if you want.

1071
01:45:22,651 --> 01:45:26,279
If we weren't prohibited from crossing
state lines in our pursuit...

1072
01:45:26,446 --> 01:45:28,114
...we'd already have him by now.

1073
01:45:28,281 --> 01:45:30,742
Well, I ain't prohibited.

1074
01:45:31,243 --> 01:45:34,830
What I'd like is for you to just stop talking
for a minute, sheriff.

1075
01:45:37,582 --> 01:45:38,875
Give me a pencil.

1076
01:45:41,002 --> 01:45:42,963
One that works.

1077
01:45:51,805 --> 01:45:54,724
What we got here is a creature of habit.

1078
01:45:55,725 --> 01:45:57,727
Unless he's changed his spots...

1079
01:45:57,894 --> 01:46:03,066
...I'd say where he'd be next is
somewhere in Missou'.

1080
01:46:08,071 --> 01:46:10,407
Thought you might be interested
in this.

1081
01:46:10,574 --> 01:46:14,411
The man Bonnie and Clyde busted out
got picked up trying to thumb a ride.

1082
01:46:14,578 --> 01:46:15,745
Where?

1083
01:46:15,912 --> 01:46:17,038
Joplin, Missouri.

1084
01:46:21,793 --> 01:46:24,421
Here. Thank you.

1085
01:46:27,883 --> 01:46:31,219
Thanks, Smoot. We'll be in touch.

1086
01:46:34,598 --> 01:46:37,642
Well, that's why
they bust you out, Ray?

1087
01:46:37,809 --> 01:46:40,979
No other jobs
they might need another gun for?

1088
01:46:41,146 --> 01:46:42,606
Yeah.

1089
01:46:42,772 --> 01:46:45,275
Told me they wanted
to track down Frank Hamer...

1090
01:46:45,442 --> 01:46:47,819
...bust a cap on him
when he was sleeping.

1091
01:46:49,237 --> 01:46:52,866
You know, Ray,
I grouse-hunt with Judge Wexler.

1092
01:46:53,033 --> 01:46:56,995
Might be worth your while
to tell us something we don't know.

1093
01:46:57,746 --> 01:46:59,456
I ain't no stool, Hamer.

1094
01:46:59,623 --> 01:47:01,917
You do right by Barrow,
but I'll tell you...

1095
01:47:02,083 --> 01:47:04,961
...he done you no favors
by busting you out of Eastham.

1096
01:47:05,128 --> 01:47:09,299
Colonel Simmons ain't fond of runners,
and he's tight with Judge Wexler.

1097
01:47:09,466 --> 01:47:13,261
I don't intervene on your behalf,
you ain't got one day left...

1098
01:47:13,470 --> 01:47:16,348
...without Simmons' thumb
stuck up your ass.

1099
01:47:19,726 --> 01:47:22,228
They were talking
about getting back into banks.

1100
01:47:22,395 --> 01:47:24,648
Getting some banks
with some real money.

1101
01:47:24,814 --> 01:47:28,777
Bonnie thought we'd pull some jobs
the size of what Pretty Boy was...

1102
01:47:28,944 --> 01:47:31,529
...we could get out of criming sooner.

1103
01:47:32,072 --> 01:47:35,241
I don't know. Probably try to find
somebody to take my place.

1104
01:47:35,408 --> 01:47:40,455
Got any specifics on which banks?
Who the somebody might be?

1105
01:47:41,373 --> 01:47:43,500
No. They kept the planning
to themselves.

1106
01:47:43,667 --> 01:47:47,879
You'd better tell me something I don't
know about Bonnie and Clyde, Ray.

1107
01:47:49,589 --> 01:47:51,174
Come on.

1108
01:47:52,050 --> 01:47:54,719
They stay in campgrounds.

1109
01:47:54,886 --> 01:47:58,932
Or just camp out,
unless Bonnie can talk Clyde out of it.

1110
01:47:59,099 --> 01:48:01,393
He tends to run careful...

1111
01:48:01,851 --> 01:48:05,730
...drive all night if he's spooked,
always the back roads.

1112
01:48:05,897 --> 01:48:09,275
Keeps a stack of license plates,
always switching them.

1113
01:48:09,442 --> 01:48:12,904
And Fords.
Clyde loves big-block Fords.

1114
01:48:13,071 --> 01:48:15,740
Won't jack a car unless it's a V-8.

1115
01:48:18,910 --> 01:48:23,206
You done us all a favor, Hamilton.
I'll talk to Wexler for you.

1116
01:48:29,921 --> 01:48:33,675
Get a mug snot of Bonnie and Clyde
to every bank in the five-state area.

1117
01:48:33,842 --> 01:48:37,012
Find out from Simmons
who Barrow consorted with in the pen...

1118
01:48:37,178 --> 01:48:38,763
...who's no longer in the pen.

1119
01:48:38,930 --> 01:48:40,306
Doubt he'd break in again.

1120
01:48:40,473 --> 01:48:44,686
See if we can get local law to keep an eye
on the cons, an eye out for Barrow.

1121
01:48:44,853 --> 01:48:46,771
There was a burglary around big D...

1122
01:48:46,938 --> 01:48:49,441
...and it wasn't just Clyde
we went looking for.

1123
01:48:49,607 --> 01:48:52,527
Should think about getting somebody
on his brother Buck.

1124
01:48:52,694 --> 01:48:55,613
Good. See it's done.

1125
01:48:57,032 --> 01:48:58,616
But where am I gonna find you?

1126
01:48:58,783 --> 01:49:02,078
If Barrow drives a V-8,
we gotta upgrade our horse.

1127
01:49:04,748 --> 01:49:06,624
On the road with Bonnie and Clyde.

1128
01:49:11,379 --> 01:49:13,089
Coming.

1129
01:49:20,930 --> 01:49:24,517
- I'll be damned.
- How you doing, big brother?

1130
01:49:25,060 --> 01:49:27,520
Good. Good. Real good.

1131
01:49:27,687 --> 01:49:29,439
You look good yourself.

1132
01:49:29,606 --> 01:49:31,232
Bonnie.

1133
01:49:31,816 --> 01:49:34,652
Well, you guys come in.
Her and Blanche can bump gums.

1134
01:49:34,819 --> 01:49:36,154
We'll all catch up.

1135
01:49:36,321 --> 01:49:40,033
Well, it may be best if you come out
to the car. Got a little hooch.

1136
01:49:40,742 --> 01:49:42,744
Come on.

1137
01:49:46,372 --> 01:49:48,374
Sit there and drink.

1138
01:49:50,126 --> 01:49:51,169
Bonnie.

1139
01:50:08,812 --> 01:50:09,896
Big money.

1140
01:50:14,109 --> 01:50:15,693
You told them no, didn't you?

1141
01:50:18,071 --> 01:50:20,782
After the whiskey,
what'd he promise you, the moon?

1142
01:50:20,949 --> 01:50:22,909
No, he didn't promise me the moon.

1143
01:50:23,076 --> 01:50:25,995
Just enough scratch
to get us a home of our own.

1144
01:50:26,162 --> 01:50:30,917
- We're doing all right without them.
- We're living at your father's house.

1145
01:50:31,084 --> 01:50:33,670
He orders me around.
We ain't doing all right.

1146
01:50:33,837 --> 01:50:36,422
- He's giving you an opportunity.
- And so is Clyde.

1147
01:50:36,589 --> 01:50:39,634
Besides, he's my brother.
He needs me to look out for him.

1148
01:50:39,801 --> 01:50:41,469
You'll both end up in prison.

1149
01:50:41,636 --> 01:50:45,473
Ain't nothing bad gonna happen,
all right, darling? Just start packing.

1150
01:50:46,724 --> 01:50:49,561
What do you think you're doing?
We're married.

1151
01:50:50,061 --> 01:50:52,105
Well, I'll write to you.

1152
01:51:11,624 --> 01:51:13,459
Daddy?

1153
01:51:17,630 --> 01:51:20,216
- She ain't Coming?
- Probably for the best.

1154
01:51:20,425 --> 01:51:22,385
All right.

1155
01:51:24,137 --> 01:51:25,763
Let's go.

1156
01:51:30,602 --> 01:51:33,396
- Daddy! Daddy!
- Looks like she changed her mind.

1157
01:51:33,563 --> 01:51:34,814
Am I stopping?

1158
01:51:50,205 --> 01:51:53,958
- You expecting any laws for supper?
- Maybe they heard you was in town.

1159
01:52:01,716 --> 01:52:04,427
Clyde the Drive.

1160
01:52:04,594 --> 01:52:05,678
Go, baby.

1161
01:52:15,313 --> 01:52:17,565
Baptism by fire, baby.

1162
01:52:23,488 --> 01:52:26,616
America 's crime wave
became a full-fledged hurricane...

1163
01:52:26,824 --> 01:52:30,745
...as Charles Arthur "Pretty Boy" Floyd
made headlines in Kansas City...

1164
01:52:31,246 --> 01:52:34,540
...committing a brazen daylight attack
to free Frank Nash...

1165
01:52:34,707 --> 01:52:37,335
...e prisoner being returned
to Leavenworth.

1166
01:52:37,877 --> 01:52:41,297
Pretty Boy and his associates
opened fire with guns blazing...

1167
01:52:41,464 --> 01:52:42,632
Why ain't we up there?

1168
01:52:42,799 --> 01:52:45,802
... outside the train station,
killing five lawmen...

1169
01:52:46,010 --> 01:52:50,223
...in what is becoming known
as the Kansas City Massacre.

1170
01:53:20,378 --> 01:53:21,462
Let's go.

1171
01:53:25,842 --> 01:53:27,677
Hands up.

1172
01:53:30,179 --> 01:53:31,514
Let's go.

1173
01:54:22,023 --> 01:54:24,233
The heck you do that for?

1174
01:54:25,026 --> 01:54:27,236
I thought I saw something.

1175
01:54:49,592 --> 01:54:51,427
Don't think the workday's over.

1176
01:54:52,637 --> 01:54:55,932
Shouldn't you be out
trying to put a bullet in someone's head?

1177
01:54:56,099 --> 01:54:58,768
You know how most outlaws get caught,
Miss Lane?

1178
01:54:58,935 --> 01:55:01,979
- Enlighten me.
- Tips.

1179
01:55:02,146 --> 01:55:03,564
From John Q. Public.

1180
01:55:03,731 --> 01:55:07,068
Problem with Bonnie and Clyde
is we're not getting any.

1181
01:55:07,777 --> 01:55:11,781
Now, I appreciate you're trying
to make your star on their skin.

1182
01:55:11,948 --> 01:55:15,618
But let me tell you the next beat
in this story of yours.

1183
01:55:15,785 --> 01:55:18,579
Pretty soon
somebody else ends up dead...

1184
01:55:18,746 --> 01:55:21,249
...and there ain't no way
you can perfume that.

1185
01:55:21,416 --> 01:55:25,711
You'll be wondering if you hadn't painted
Bonnie and Clyde like Garbo and Gable...

1186
01:55:25,878 --> 01:55:28,756
...maybe somebody
would've stepped forward...

1187
01:55:28,923 --> 01:55:32,510
...and this husband or that father
wouldn't be dead at all.

1188
01:55:32,677 --> 01:55:35,138
If I don't write this story,
someone else will.

1189
01:55:35,304 --> 01:55:39,142
I suppose, but I don't see anybody else
throwing out these photo spreads.

1190
01:55:39,308 --> 01:55:42,478
- How'd you run across these pictures?
- I'm good at what I do.

1191
01:55:42,645 --> 01:55:44,313
I don't compromise my sources.

1192
01:55:44,522 --> 01:55:47,859
I'm gonna need to see
the uncropped versions of these.

1193
01:55:48,025 --> 01:55:49,986
I'm not inclined to give them to you.

