1431
02:17:21,776 --> 02:17:25,363
And I was right there behind her,
and I sure didn't see no gun.

1432
02:18:09,199 --> 02:18:12,952
Gotta go, gotta go. Buck?
Buck, we got company.

1433
02:18:13,161 --> 02:18:15,330
- Daddy?
- Get the light, get the light.

1434
02:18:15,497 --> 02:18:16,831
Daddy, what's going on?

1435
02:18:24,631 --> 02:18:26,174
L-Hey.

1436
02:18:38,645 --> 02:18:41,064
Get down. Get down.

1437
02:18:42,148 --> 02:18:44,984
This is the police.
We've got you surrounded.

1438
02:18:45,151 --> 02:18:46,694
Come out with your hands up.

1439
02:18:56,329 --> 02:18:59,916
You got one minute to exit the building.

1440
02:19:03,002 --> 02:19:05,964
- Stay low. Grab our stuff.
- All right, all right.

1441
02:19:53,219 --> 02:19:55,972
- No.
- Leave the damn box.

1442
02:19:56,139 --> 02:19:58,683
No. No, I'm not leaving it. No.

1443
02:20:00,518 --> 02:20:01,936
The hell you doing?

1444
02:20:04,606 --> 02:20:06,816
Let's go. Let's get going.

1445
02:20:27,795 --> 02:20:29,130
Daddy!

1446
02:20:29,631 --> 02:20:31,341
No, Daddy!

1447
02:20:32,258 --> 02:20:34,010
Come on.

1448
02:20:43,186 --> 02:20:44,729
Come on.

1449
02:20:50,068 --> 02:20:54,197
What the hell were you doing,
cutting your damn toenails?

1450
02:20:56,532 --> 02:21:00,370
No, Daddy! No, Daddy!

1451
02:21:00,578 --> 02:21:01,996
Daddy, no.

1452
02:21:02,163 --> 02:21:05,208
Daddy, no. No!

1453
02:21:06,167 --> 02:21:09,337
Daddy, no! No, Daddy!

1454
02:21:09,963 --> 02:21:11,965
Go on! Go on!

1455
02:21:22,266 --> 02:21:23,851
Daddy!

1456
02:21:54,799 --> 02:21:56,551
- Howdy.
- Evening.

1457
02:21:57,176 --> 02:21:59,012
Evening to you.

1458
02:22:00,388 --> 02:22:01,514
If I could get some...

1459
02:22:01,681 --> 02:22:04,976
Just a can of coffee and some beans...

1460
02:22:05,143 --> 02:22:07,353
...and a loaf of that bread there too.

1461
02:22:10,106 --> 02:22:12,316
Some ice. I could use some ice.

1462
02:22:12,984 --> 02:22:14,527
Yeah.

1463
02:22:16,279 --> 02:22:19,699
Yeah, also some of those bandages
over there too.

1464
02:22:21,075 --> 02:22:25,705
And how about a can
of that lighter fluid right there?

1465
02:22:25,913 --> 02:22:27,832
Yeah.

1466
02:22:27,999 --> 02:22:29,667
Is that it?

1467
02:22:30,460 --> 02:22:34,672
- What's the damage?
- That'll be 1.75.

1468
02:22:38,051 --> 02:22:39,802
All right.

1469
02:22:42,388 --> 02:22:46,017
- Can I help you with that?
- No, no, no. Oh, my...

1470
02:22:46,184 --> 02:22:49,937
Yeah, I sprained my shoulder
playing baseball with friends.

1471
02:22:50,104 --> 02:22:51,898
Yeah.

1472
02:22:52,065 --> 02:22:54,067
Keep the change.

1473
02:23:15,004 --> 02:23:18,424
We brought everything we had
and gave it good.

1474
02:23:18,591 --> 02:23:20,802
They just got lucky.

1475
02:23:21,302 --> 02:23:23,054
Lucky?

1476
02:23:25,890 --> 02:23:29,227
Unless I'm mistaken,
didn't you and I have a conversation...

1477
02:23:29,393 --> 02:23:33,523
...that I'd be here in the morning
and take charge of the apprehension?

1478
02:23:33,689 --> 02:23:37,318
We had reason to believe
that they might be gone come morning.

1479
02:23:37,485 --> 02:23:39,070
Really?

1480
02:23:39,487 --> 02:23:42,865
Had nothing to do with you
wanting to make a name for yourself...

1481
02:23:43,032 --> 02:23:45,243
...by collaring Bonnie and Clyde?

1482
02:23:47,328 --> 02:23:50,832
It was like nothing I've ever seen.
It was like the Fourth of July.

1483
02:23:50,998 --> 02:23:54,544
It was Bonnie doing the shooting.
I only saw her for an instant.

1484
02:23:55,294 --> 02:23:58,297
I'll never forget her.
She was the one firing that tommy.

1485
02:24:02,802 --> 02:24:04,971
Good girl, Ted?

1486
02:24:07,515 --> 02:24:09,267
Jesus, you're sweet on her.

1487
02:24:11,519 --> 02:24:13,312
Just got word out of Iowa.

1488
02:24:13,479 --> 02:24:16,816
Clerk at a market, works as a marshal,
just ID'd Clyde Barrow.

1489
02:24:16,983 --> 02:24:19,986
- You tell them to wait till I got there?
- Tried...

1490
02:24:20,153 --> 02:24:22,446
...but my deputy heard it
from a dispatcher.

1491
02:24:22,613 --> 02:24:25,867
Sounds like the train...
Damn big one, from what he understood.

1492
02:24:26,033 --> 02:24:27,285
... just left the station.

1493
02:24:27,451 --> 02:24:31,914
Why's every idiot with a badge
gotta try to out-idiot the other?

1494
02:24:43,509 --> 02:24:45,094
It's cold, Bonnie. We're cold.

1495
02:24:49,390 --> 02:24:52,768
Got a good fire burning now.
It'll be okay.

1496
02:24:53,936 --> 02:24:55,771
Can't take no more of Daddy's hurt.

1497
02:24:56,939 --> 02:24:59,775
Gotta do something
about Daddy's hurt.

1498
02:25:04,322 --> 02:25:06,157
Put some ice on his head.

1499
02:25:06,324 --> 02:25:08,743
Should take down the swelling,
ease his pain.

1500
02:25:08,910 --> 02:25:11,245
There's also bandages
in the other one.

1501
02:25:11,412 --> 02:25:15,416
- Can't hardly see, Clyde.
- I was talking to Bonnie.

1502
02:25:26,302 --> 02:25:29,805
Your brother walked five miles into town
to get you this ice, Buck.

1503
02:25:33,935 --> 02:25:37,563
- Gonna get you home.
- Don't got a home.

1504
02:25:42,026 --> 02:25:44,904
Daddy. Daddy.

1505
02:25:58,668 --> 02:26:00,086
No!

1506
02:26:03,506 --> 02:26:04,840
No.

1507
02:26:20,856 --> 02:26:22,066
Mama.

1508
02:26:23,567 --> 02:26:25,194
Mama.

1509
02:27:08,321 --> 02:27:09,864
They're coming.

1510
02:27:11,949 --> 02:27:14,410
Come on. Wake up right now.
They're coming.

1511
02:27:17,913 --> 02:27:21,667
Daddy. Daddy, come on.
Come on, wake up.

1512
02:27:23,085 --> 02:27:26,005
Come on. Coming right now.

1513
02:27:32,720 --> 02:27:34,263
Ready.

1514
02:27:36,390 --> 02:27:38,100
Fire!

1515
02:28:02,124 --> 02:28:03,167
Everybody out.

1516
02:28:10,925 --> 02:28:12,802
- Daddy. Daddy, come on.
- Come on.

1517
02:28:19,558 --> 02:28:21,560
- Down by the creek.
- Go on, go on.

1518
02:28:34,156 --> 02:28:35,908
I'm on them.

1519
02:29:19,452 --> 02:29:23,372
No! Daddy!

1520
02:29:24,081 --> 02:29:25,791
L-Hey.

1521
02:29:25,958 --> 02:29:29,128
Barrow, that's enough. It's over.

1522
02:29:29,295 --> 02:29:34,049
No, Buck. Clyde, help us, please.

1523
02:29:34,216 --> 02:29:36,469
- Please. No.
- Drop your weapon.

1524
02:29:36,635 --> 02:29:38,888
Come out with your hands up.

1525
02:29:41,223 --> 02:29:43,184
Do you hear me, Barrow?

1526
02:29:46,187 --> 02:29:49,815
You're finished, Barrow! Come on out!

1527
02:29:52,359 --> 02:29:53,486
No.

1528
02:30:05,623 --> 02:30:08,209
No, please.

1529
02:30:09,168 --> 02:30:10,294
No.

1530
02:30:43,285 --> 02:30:45,621
No laws are after us, Clyde.

1531
02:30:48,791 --> 02:30:50,292
Listen.

1532
02:30:52,753 --> 02:30:56,632
I loved Buck. I couldn't be more sorry
about what happened to him.

1533
02:30:56,799 --> 02:30:58,384
Well, look on the bright side.

1534
02:30:58,551 --> 02:31:01,929
- You'll probably get a nice headline.
- That isn't fair.

1535
02:31:02,096 --> 02:31:06,559
What isn't fair is my brother lying back
there with half his damn head blown off.

1536
02:31:06,725 --> 02:31:10,312
- I didn't want him involved.
- Well, he got involved.

1537
02:31:14,817 --> 02:31:17,486
And even if he dies...

1538
02:31:17,945 --> 02:31:20,447
...people are gonna remember him.

1539
02:31:21,991 --> 02:31:23,576
Clyde...

1540
02:31:23,742 --> 02:31:27,580
...Buck got to be a part of something,
something bigger than all of us.

1541
02:31:27,746 --> 02:31:30,708
You know now many people get nothing
but 60 years...

1542
02:31:30,874 --> 02:31:32,710
...of nobody knowing they're alive?

1543
02:31:32,876 --> 02:31:36,964
- Absolutely nothing?
- And that's all you care about, isn't it?

1544
02:31:37,131 --> 02:31:39,133
People knowing who you are.

1545
02:31:39,300 --> 02:31:43,220
I said you weren't a horrible person,
Bonnie, but I was wrong.

1546
02:31:43,387 --> 02:31:45,889
You don't care about Buck.

1547
02:31:46,056 --> 02:31:48,142
You don't love me.

1548
02:31:48,309 --> 02:31:52,271
No, I'm just a footnote
in the story of you.

1549
02:31:52,438 --> 02:31:55,274
Every time the blood was leaking out
of some bastard...

1550
02:31:55,441 --> 02:31:59,862
...you figured just as much ink flowed to
building up the legend of Bonnie Parker.

1551
02:32:01,196 --> 02:32:04,700
And Christmas,
that wasn't cause for mercy, was it?

1552
02:32:04,867 --> 02:32:08,537
No, that was just reason for the papers
to print your picture bigger.

1553
02:32:08,704 --> 02:32:10,956
You never saw a goddamn gun,
did you?

1554
02:32:11,582 --> 02:32:14,501
- Did you? Did you?
- Clyde!

1555
02:32:27,097 --> 02:32:28,682
Bonnie.

1556
02:32:40,486 --> 02:32:43,822
Get me out, get me out, get me out!

1557
02:32:58,754 --> 02:33:00,714
Right through here.

1558
02:33:25,406 --> 02:33:27,157
Daddy.

1559
02:33:31,286 --> 02:33:35,040
At least one of them got banged up,
maybe burned.

1560
02:33:35,207 --> 02:33:37,835
They'll be looking for safe harbor.

1561
02:33:40,546 --> 02:33:44,007
I wanna get word out to every
gang member ever worked with them...

1562
02:33:44,174 --> 02:33:47,094
...to the families
of all the gang members...

1563
02:33:47,261 --> 02:33:51,223
...there's full pardons and reward money
for anyone who gives up Barrow.

1564
02:33:53,142 --> 02:33:56,395
Well, I hope someone does.
Been on this a while.

1565
02:33:58,105 --> 02:34:00,149
And we'll be on it...

1566
02:34:00,983 --> 02:34:02,901
...till it's finished.

1567
02:34:21,044 --> 02:34:22,796
Gonna get you better, Bon.

1568
02:34:27,134 --> 02:34:30,304
You should have just let me burn.

1569
02:34:32,931 --> 02:34:37,144
If you meant even half of what you said,
I got no reason to keep breathing.

1570
02:34:37,311 --> 02:34:39,521
You got every reason.

1571
02:34:50,240 --> 02:34:51,992
Hush now.

1572
02:35:08,300 --> 02:35:11,345
Remember when Clyde
didn't even trust you to be a lookout?

1573
02:35:12,179 --> 02:35:15,224
Pretty Boy himself would run away
if he ran into you now.

1574
02:35:15,390 --> 02:35:18,936
Probably loves you, though.
You pushed him right off the front page.

1575
02:35:21,146 --> 02:35:24,107
Pretty keen on staying
out of the limelight now, Henry.

1576
02:35:24,274 --> 02:35:26,401
Understood.

1577
02:35:26,568 --> 02:35:29,321
No better place to do it
than Nowhere, Louisiana.

1578
02:35:29,488 --> 02:35:32,366
Really appreciate you putting us up.

1579
02:35:32,533 --> 02:35:35,369
Hell, ain't no skin off my teeth.

1580
02:35:35,536 --> 02:35:37,621
It's a honor to do it.

1581
02:35:38,288 --> 02:35:41,041
Sure your father doesn't mind
us bunking down here?

1582
02:35:41,208 --> 02:35:42,501
Don't worry about him.

1583
02:35:42,668 --> 02:35:45,003
Hiding three fugitives
is no harder than one.

1584
02:35:45,170 --> 02:35:47,923
You keep us in groceries,
he'll be happy enough.

1585
02:35:51,802 --> 02:35:55,556
Hell, breakfast with Bonnie and Clyde.

1586
02:36:00,519 --> 02:36:02,521
I had a dream, Cly.

1587
02:36:02,688 --> 02:36:05,941
- What'd you dream about?
- Johnny.

1588
02:36:06,108 --> 02:36:12,197
He was the cutest little thing,
all bundled in his crib and laughing.

1589
02:36:13,866 --> 02:36:16,159
Not a care in the world.

1590
02:36:17,744 --> 02:36:20,122
I dreamed we had a baby.

1591
02:36:21,248 --> 02:36:24,960
Johnny didn't have his father's
funny little nose, did he?

1592
02:36:25,878 --> 02:36:30,340
He had the most perfect nose,
curly blond hair.

1593
02:36:30,507 --> 02:36:32,175
Blond?

1594
02:36:32,843 --> 02:36:35,095
And pretty green eyes like his daddy.

1595
02:36:41,727 --> 02:36:43,937
Iverson Methvin.

1596
02:36:45,439 --> 02:36:48,233
Yeah, I got them both.

1597
02:36:52,946 --> 02:36:57,659
You sure you can make everything my
boy's done dirty come clean, Mr. Hamer?

1598
02:36:58,952 --> 02:37:01,163
I don't know how much longer.

1599
02:37:01,330 --> 02:37:03,206
A few days, maybe a week.

1600
02:37:03,373 --> 02:37:05,542
She ain't doing real good.

1601
02:37:08,086 --> 02:37:12,049
Okay. There's a reward, right?

1602
02:37:12,925 --> 02:37:16,219
Bienville Parish, Louisiana.

1603
02:37:28,357 --> 02:37:31,860
- Where we going, Clyde?
- Texas.

1604
02:37:32,027 --> 02:37:35,697
Figure we should see your family,
your mama and mine...

1605
02:37:35,864 --> 02:37:38,033
...get some new clothes.

1606
02:37:38,408 --> 02:37:41,995
But you bought that Easter ham
for the Methvins.

1607
02:37:42,162 --> 02:37:46,166
Yeah, we pretty much played out
our welcome.

1608
02:37:48,377 --> 02:37:50,963
Mama will be so happy to see us.

1609
02:37:53,882 --> 02:37:57,177
Yeah, you are so cute.

1610
02:38:02,766 --> 02:38:04,643
Missed that one.

1611
02:38:05,894 --> 02:38:09,106
They were selling
these little darlings, Clyde.

1612
02:38:09,272 --> 02:38:11,858
They were practically
giving them away.

1613
02:38:12,025 --> 02:38:14,236
No, I don't like rabbits. They're dirty.

1614
02:38:14,403 --> 02:38:17,364
He's a heck of a lot cleaner than you.

1615
02:38:17,531 --> 02:38:19,825
I don't want that thing in the car.

1616
02:38:21,284 --> 02:38:24,204
It's a present for my mama, Clyde.

1617
02:38:26,873 --> 02:38:29,042
Fine, if that's how you feel...

1618
02:38:29,209 --> 02:38:32,254
...just take the dirty little bunny
and give it back.

1619
02:38:47,644 --> 02:38:51,106
- What you drinking, Mama?
- Whatever I please.

1620
02:38:51,273 --> 02:38:54,192
It don't look to be pleasing you.
You look miserable.

1621
02:38:54,359 --> 02:38:57,863
What in the hell would I have
to be miserable about?

1622
02:38:59,740 --> 02:39:01,992
It ain't helping anyway.

1623
02:39:02,159 --> 02:39:04,870
I ought to get me
some of whatever pharmaceutical...

1624
02:39:05,037 --> 02:39:08,457
...Roy Thornton's wife's
floating on over there.

1625
02:39:10,417 --> 02:39:11,752
She's in a lot of pain.

1626
02:39:11,918 --> 02:39:16,673
Pretty sure the two of you have given
a lot more than you've gotten.

1627
02:39:20,177 --> 02:39:25,724
These days with the suns,
those are the days you'd come visit.

1628
02:39:25,891 --> 02:39:30,520
No matter what you did, I was always
happy to see my little ray of sunshine.

1629
02:39:31,521 --> 02:39:35,817
But Buck, he was trying to be good.

1630
02:39:35,984 --> 02:39:40,072
The fact that you done so much bad,
you couldn't go to your brother's funeral.

1631
02:39:40,238 --> 02:39:42,991
- Mom.
- You're the reason he's dead and buried.

1632
02:39:43,158 --> 02:39:47,496
Not the oops that shot him,
not the fates.

1633
02:39:47,662 --> 02:39:49,706
It's just you.

1634
02:40:13,522 --> 02:40:16,733
Look at your cute little ears.

1635
02:40:17,651 --> 02:40:20,779
I was thinking we need to start
weaning you off that Amytal.

1636
02:40:20,946 --> 02:40:26,201
You are so cute.
Mama's just gonna eat you up.

1637
02:40:26,368 --> 02:40:28,245
You hear what I'm saying?

1638
02:40:28,995 --> 02:40:34,417
Yeah, but right now I've just gotta say,
it's just making things easier.

1639
02:40:35,752 --> 02:40:36,878
You know what?

1640
02:40:37,045 --> 02:40:40,048
Mama's not gonna appreciate you
near as much as us.

1641
02:40:40,215 --> 02:40:44,136
We're gonna keep you, sonny boy.
What do you think about that?

1642
02:40:56,523 --> 02:40:57,941
L-Hey.

1643
02:41:13,498 --> 02:41:16,418
- You folks all right?
- We're as right as right can be.

1644
02:41:16,585 --> 02:41:18,128
Just enjoying the day.

1645
02:41:18,295 --> 02:41:21,840
Fixing to have a little picnic
just over there by that tree.

1646
02:41:23,508 --> 02:41:26,595
- That's a fine enough spot for that, right?
- Yep.

1647
02:41:26,761 --> 02:41:29,347
- Just wanted to make sure you're okay.
- Thank you.

1648
02:41:29,514 --> 02:41:31,099
All right. Happy Easter, miss.

1649
02:42:31,576 --> 02:42:33,745
See how his head bounced, Clyde?

1650
02:42:36,706 --> 02:42:38,667
Just like a rubber ball.

1651
02:42:44,214 --> 02:42:46,841
The Lord is my shepherd.
I shall not want.

1652
02:42:47,008 --> 02:42:50,053
He maketh me to lie down
in green pastures.

1653
02:42:50,220 --> 02:42:52,222
He leadeth me beside the still waters.

1654
02:42:52,931 --> 02:42:54,766
He restoreth my soul.

1655
02:42:54,933 --> 02:42:58,979
He leadeth me in the paths
of righteousness for his name's sake.

1656
02:42:59,145 --> 02:43:02,440
Yea, though I walk through the valley
of the shadow of death...

1657
02:43:02,607 --> 02:43:05,360
...I will fear no evil,
for though art with me.

1658
02:43:05,527 --> 02:43:09,489
Thy rod and thy staff they comfort me.
Thou preparest a table before me ....

1659
02:43:09,656 --> 02:43:12,993
My great-grandma said the Good Book
called the apple Eve ate...

1660
02:43:13,159 --> 02:43:15,287
"the fruit of knowledge."

1661
02:43:16,121 --> 02:43:18,581
I never understood
why knowledge was thought...

1662
02:43:18,748 --> 02:43:20,792
...to be the root of so much suffering.

1663
02:43:20,959 --> 02:43:24,963
The ongoing saga of Bonnie and Clyde
took another dark turn Easter Sunday...

1664
02:43:25,130 --> 02:43:28,842
...es two lawmen, E.B. Wheeler and
Holloway Murphy, were gunned down...

1665
02:43:29,009 --> 02:43:32,137
...outside the notorious outlaw couple's
hometown of Dallas.

1666
02:43:32,304 --> 02:43:36,182
Wheeler's widow, slated to marry
the man the following weekend...

1667
02:43:36,349 --> 02:43:40,103
...found herself wearing her wedding
gown to a much less festive affair.

1668
02:43:40,270 --> 02:43:44,274
And while Bonnie and Clyde had
at one time been virtual folk heroes...

1669
02:43:44,441 --> 02:43:48,403
...e rancher who witnessed the event
was fer from impressed.

1670
02:43:48,570 --> 02:43:54,326
After she shot that lawman, she said,
"See how his head bounced, Clyde?

1671
02:43:54,492 --> 02:43:57,329
Like a rubber ball."
That's what she said.

1672
02:43:58,288 --> 02:43:59,706
Do you believe that?

1673
02:43:59,873 --> 02:44:03,168
"Like a rubber ball. " Man, oh, man.

1674
02:44:03,335 --> 02:44:07,005
The hunt continues for Bonnie
and Clyde, believed to be in Louisiana.

1675
02:44:07,172 --> 02:44:10,300
Police have set up roadblocks
on all roads to other states.

1676
02:44:10,467 --> 02:44:15,513
But on that Easter Sunday,
I tasted the apple.

1677
02:44:16,556 --> 02:44:19,142
And the knowledge it gave me...

1678
02:44:19,309 --> 02:44:21,686
...of what I needed to do...

1679
02:44:22,812 --> 02:44:25,065
wasn't sweet at all.

1680
02:44:54,719 --> 02:44:56,596
Methvin residence.

1681
02:44:57,806 --> 02:44:59,349
Yeah.

1682
02:45:01,601 --> 02:45:03,520
It's Clyde Barrow.

1683
02:45:04,312 --> 02:45:07,107
Yeah. All right, I'll see you then.

1684
02:45:10,402 --> 02:45:14,906
- Hamer.
- This is Methvin, Iverson.

1685
02:45:15,740 --> 02:45:19,536
Everything's been arranged.
Barrow's on his way here.

1686
02:45:20,286 --> 02:45:23,957
- Should be here in a couple of days.
- Thank you, Mr. Methvin.

1687
02:45:24,707 --> 02:45:28,002
We'll make good on our promises
to your boy.

1688
02:45:40,557 --> 02:45:43,685
What are we doing back here,
Clyde Champion?

1689
02:45:44,144 --> 02:45:48,148
Called Methvin while you were dozing.
Gonna pick him up.

1690
02:45:49,023 --> 02:45:51,985
Figure we could pull a few jobs
in Louisiana...

1691
02:45:52,152 --> 02:45:54,779
...maybe push into Arkansas.

1692
02:45:55,321 --> 02:45:57,991
Nobody knows us in Arkansas.

1693
02:45:58,158 --> 02:46:02,412
Too soon to be thinking about retiring
to that lake home, huh?

1694
02:46:03,037 --> 02:46:04,289
Not just yet.

1695
02:46:11,296 --> 02:46:14,048
You know what I been thinking, Clyde?

1696
02:46:14,215 --> 02:46:18,386
- I ain't no mind reader.
- We should lie in wait for him.

1697
02:46:18,887 --> 02:46:21,848
- Who?
- Frank Hamer.

1698
02:46:22,640 --> 02:46:26,769
Put one in him
instead of the other way around.

1699
02:46:28,229 --> 02:46:32,108
- Get us a hell of a headline too, huh?
- Who gives two damns about that?

1700
02:46:32,275 --> 02:46:36,029
Just be nice
to be able to sleep better at night.

1701
02:46:38,490 --> 02:46:40,408
Yeah.

1702
02:47:04,682 --> 02:47:06,684
Something wrong, Clyde?

1703
02:47:07,227 --> 02:47:08,603
No.

1704
02:47:09,729 --> 02:47:12,857
Just enjoying now beautiful
everything is.

1705
02:47:34,504 --> 02:47:36,005
You don't have to shoot, Ted.

1706
02:47:37,048 --> 02:47:40,510
Yeah, Frank, I do.

1707
02:47:40,969 --> 02:47:43,179
That's Methvin's truck, isn't it?

1708
02:47:58,736 --> 02:47:59,779
Clyde?

1709
02:48:05,285 --> 02:48:07,954
I've always loved you, Bonnie.

1710
02:50:09,617 --> 02:50:12,120
Mr. Hamer.

1711
02:50:14,205 --> 02:50:18,376
Mr. Hamer, you shot them down
in cold blood?

1712
02:50:18,543 --> 02:50:22,380
What do you say to the accusations
you shot them down in cold blood?

1713
02:50:22,547 --> 02:50:24,382
You think it was fair, Mr. Hamer...

1714
02:50:24,549 --> 02:50:28,344
...that you didn't give Bonnie and Clyde
a warning, just executed them?

1715
02:50:29,804 --> 02:50:33,266
Ma'am, I'm afraid
what we all gave Bonnie and Clyde...

1716
02:50:33,433 --> 02:50:36,352
...was exactly what they wanted.

1717
02:50:37,145 --> 02:50:39,689
Mr. Hamer, Mr. Hamer.

1718
02:50:49,532 --> 02:50:53,619
Sometimes I like to think
that fever of unexplained origin...

1719
02:50:53,786 --> 02:50:57,540
...that I never came out
of the other side...

1720
02:50:57,707 --> 02:51:02,295
...end the rest of my life,
none of it ever happened.

1721
02:51:03,045 --> 02:51:07,425
Especially that part
where I got shot 37 times...

1722
02:51:08,134 --> 02:51:12,597
giving my Bonnie Parker
her big ending.